<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislative Council Meeting Adopts Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Legislative Council
adopted a motion on the alleviation of the hardship of people's
livelihood during its meeting here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The motion urges the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
government to adopt effective measures to alleviate hardship of
people's livelihood and formulate a long-term industrial policy to
advance Hong Kong's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The measures include the reduction of the petrol tax by 30
percent, returning 20 percent of the salaries tax and profits tax
paid for the year 1996-97 and the establishment of a Social
Welfare Services Development Fund to implement its commitments to
social welfare services, and increase employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Another motion on unemployment failed to earn enough votes
after long debates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the council members had the first and second
readings of the Holidays (Amendment) Bill 1998.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the bill is to replace two of the general
holidays observed in 1997 and 1998, that is, Sino-Japanese War
Victory Day (the third Monday in August) and October 2 (the day
after the National Day), by Labor Day (May 1) and the Buddha's
Birthday (eighth day of the fourth lunar month) from 1999 onwards.
</P>
<P>
The meeting lasted for more than nine hours. In the course,
government officials answered nearly 20 questions on various
policy areas raised by legislators in oral or written form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
