<HEADLINE> Roundup: London Links With Frankfurt for Single </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The London and Frankfurt stock
exchanges are to join forces, a historic agreement which will pave
the way for a single European stock market.
</P>
<P>
The two exchanges Tuesday signed a memorandum of understanding
and outlined details of a strategic alliance. They are to create a
50/50 joint venture, and will work together to develop a
pan-European stock market.
</P>
<P>
Details of which companies will be included have yet to be
decided. However, based on the current FTSE Eurotop 300 index, a
Stock Exchange spokesman said they would include 108 UK-based
stocks and 37 German stocks.
</P>
<P>
The move ends a bitter war between the two exchanges for
supremacy in Europe's rapidly converging financial markets and
also represents a sharp reversal of policy for the London
exchange, which has until recently rebuffed any suggestion that it
should cooperate with other markets.
</P>
<P>
It marks a watershed in relations between London and Frankfurt.
Werner Seifert, chief executive of the Deutsche Borse, said he
wanted to "end all speculation about a battle between London and
Frankfurt, which was never intended on either side."
</P>
<P>
The announcement surprised the Paris stock exchange, which had
been working on plans for cooperation with Frankfurt and appears
to be left in the cold by the London and Frankfurt alliance.
</P>
<P>
The London Stock Exchange and the Deutsche Borse said they
hoped to form a "core nucleus" around which a pan-European stock
market would be based.
</P>
<P>
John Kemp-Welch, chairman of the London Stock Exchange, said
Tuesday that he had spoken to a number of chairmen and chief
executives of other European bourses and that they were all very
interested in the concept.
</P>
<P>
The two exchanges are to start work immediately on setting up a
common access package, which will allow the shares of the top 300
European companies to be traded on either exchange.
</P>
<P>
They plan to harmonize their market rules, accounting standards
and conventions and eventually build a single electronic trading
system.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was applauded by investment banks, regulators
and investors in Europe. Large fund managers have already begun to
treat Europe as a single market for investment purposes, and this
should accelerate with the euro's launch next year.
</P>
<P>
Werner Seifert said that as these forces created a global
capital market, the alliance with London was "a logical answer to
the marginalization of national and local financial centers."
</P>
<P>
At present, London is the second-largest stock market in the
world, behind the United State, while Germany is ranked second in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover in London last year was 889 billion pounds
(1422.4 billion U.S. dollars), compared to 462 billion pounds
(739.2 billion dollars) in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly believed in the City that the agreement is an
important move for European markets, as well as London and
Frankfurt, and will ensure that they remain well placed to
maintain and enhance their position as one of the leading
financial centers of the world.
</P>
<P>
However, a few observers said, as the merger process will take
quite a time, some doubts will still linger among broking houses
and dealers. They want to see how it all works before they
applaud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
