<HEADLINE> Widespread Violence Takes Place in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 200 attacks have been made
against the security forces in Northern Ireland in the last 24
hours, the Northern Irish police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest incidents take the number of attacks since the
Drumcree stand-off began Sunday to more than 430.
</P>
<P>
That figure includes 12 shootings and 25 bombings, the police
said. Dozens of cars and buses have also been hijacked and burnt.
</P>
<P>
The new wave of gun and bomb attacks undermined efforts to
resolve a crisis over a Protestant parade banned from marching
through the Garvaghy Road in Portadown, 50 km southwest of
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The decision to ban the Orangemen was taken by the independent
Parades Commission which wanted to avoid the kind of violence that
could wreck Northern Ireland's fragile peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said Wednesday
the Orange Order was deliberately trying to stretch the security
forces.
</P>
<P>
"It is not enough to call for peaceful protest, if at the same
time you are not abiding by the law," she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair will meet with the Orangemen Thursday
about the stand-off between the marchers and the police, but a
breakthrough about the crisis is unlikely as Blair said the ban on
the parade was not open for discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
