<HEADLINE> Jordan, South Africa Discuss Trade, Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy Foreign Minister
Aziz Pahad held talks with Jordanian officials here Wednesday on
ways of boosting bilateral trade as well as their coordination in
reviving the stalled Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is Pahad' first leg of a Mideast tour, which will also
include trips to Egypt, Israel and Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival here Wednesday, Pahad met Jordanian Minister
of Industry and Trade Hani Mulki to discuss how to promote the
bilateral ties in trade, tourism and agricultural fields, Jordan's
official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Pahad and Mulki also discussed the possibility of conducting
cooperation between the two countries within the framework of the
international non-aligned movement.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is to host a summit of The Non-Aligned Movement
in late August.
</P>
<P>
During his six-day stay in Jordan, Pahad is also expected to
meet more Jordanian officials to discuss other bilateral issues
and their roles in reviving the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the South African Embassy here said
Pahad would also discuss with Egyptian leaders the upcoming summit
in his country and find ways to overcome differences over the
faltering peace process.
</P>
<P>
The release stated that South Africa hoped to play "a potential
role to bridge the gap between the Palestinians and Israelis."
</P>
<P>
It added that Pahad's visit was conducted after South Africa
received a number of appeals from various participants in the Oslo
process to help advance the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel maintained close ties with South Africa's former
apartheid government before the present President Nelson Mandela
came to power in the country's first all-race elections in 1994,
the semi-official Jordan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But the current South African government identifies with the
Palestinian struggle for liberation, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
