<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Minister Stresses Need of Education for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Minister of State for Women
Development and Social Welfare and Special Education Tehmina
Daultana Wednesday emphasized the need to educate the mothers "if
we want to build better and literate society to meet the
challenges of the next century."
</P>
<P>
Tehmina was speaking here at the launching of a U.N. report --
"The Progress of Nations 1998" -- with special emphasis on the
registration of child at the time of birth.
</P>
<P>
She said that ignoring a girl child means that half of the
population is being ignored. How can a country make progress while
ignoring half of its population, she added.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF (U.N. Children's Fund) has described the world's
children as the "forgotten quarter" of the Earth's people.
</P>
<P>
The convention on the rights of the child has provided a
standard benchmark against which the behavior of the nation is
measured and improved, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has made certain laws to curb child
labor according to its commitment. But the implementation of these
laws is the most important thing. It can only be done with the
help of the people, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
She said it is the responsibility of all Pakistani people to
make sure the implementation of these laws.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the idea of registration of newly born baby with
the registration office, she appreciated the efforts of UNICEF,
saying that "it is something which every one of us should take
care of."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, different presentations were made to highlight the
child immunization program, condition of girl child and the
tendency to register the child at the time of birth.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the Ministry of Women Development Muzaffar Mehmood
Qureshi placed special emphasis on the registration of child.
</P>
<P>
"For this purpose, it is necessary to instruct the registration
officers and to guide the parents and apprise them of the
advantages of registration of child," said Qureshi.
</P>
<P>
He said that UNICEF has done a lot in this regard and
particularly this organization is helping Pakistan in many ways.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF Representative to Pakistan Stephen H. Umemoto said on
the occasion that the report will be launched across the world and
in the next few days it will be launched in 145 countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that according to the report almost 40 million children
every year are not registered, despite the fact that Article 7 of
the Convention on the Rights of Child clearly says, "the child
shall be registered immediately after birth."
</P>
<P>
He said despite almost universal ratification of this human
rights treaty, one third of all births go un-registered.
</P>
<P>
In Pakistan, the birth certificate is only needed by the school
administration if one intends to get his/her child admitted to
school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
