<HEADLINE> Museveni on Visit to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has ended his short working visit to Ethiopia and Eritrea and
left for South Africa Wednesday to hold talks with President
Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Museveni arrived at Water Kroof Air Base in Pretoria Wednesday
afternoon and was warmly received by S. African Foreign Minister
Alfred Nzo and Uganda's High Commissioner to South Africa Edward
Rugumayo, a press release said.
</P>
<P>
The press release issued here Wednesday, however, did not
mention the topics of their talks to be held at Mandela's
residence, but it is believed that Museveni would brief Mandela
on the result of his mediation between Addis and Asmara.
</P>
<P>
After Museveni held talks with Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi Tuesday evening, Ugandan First Deputy Prime Minister Eriya
Kategaya who was accompanying the president told reporters that
the two leaders had held frank and friendly discussions on
matters of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Museveni called his trip to the Horn of Africa an addition to
the international and regional efforts to end the armed conflict
between Ethiopia and Eritrea over a strip of border area.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan president went to Eritrea for a two-day visit
before proceeding to Ethiopia. 
</P>
