<HEADLINE> Pak Population at 130.58 Million: Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz
announced here Wednesday that Pakistan's total population has
reached 130.58 million, showing an average annual growth rate of
2.61 percent since 1981.
</P>
<P>
"I can claim it as the most authentic, fair and transparent
Census in the history of Pakistan," Aziz said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth Population and Housing Census 1998 was undertaken
from March 2 to 18 throughout the country. About 150,000 field
staff were hired from the provincial government departments and
imparted thorough training before the census operations.
</P>
<P>
The provisional result showed that the total population of
130.58 million in this South Asian nation was 46.326 million more
than that of the last Population and Housing Census conducted in
1981.
</P>
<P>
This shows an overall percentage increase of 54.98 over the
last census, recording an average growth rate of 2.61 percent as
against 3.06 observed during 1971-81.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the population is well below 138 million as was being
assumed before, adding it is a welcome decline in the rate of
population growth in all areas except Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
This was an understandable increase due to in-migration of
population since becoming the capital of Pakistan, the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
He said though the annual average growth rate during 1981- 98
is 2.61 percent, it is lower in the recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to the results, the population of Pakistan's largest
province of Punjab has been placed at 72.585 million as against
47.292 million. This shows an annual growth rate of 2.55 percent
as against the 2.74 observed during 1971-81.
</P>
<P>
Sindh's population, under the new Census, is 29.991 million
which shows an annual growth rate of 2.71 percent. In the last
Census, Sindh's population was 19.029 million with an annual
growth rate of 3.56 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
