<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Makes Room for CTBT Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- India created room for
negotiations with the five nuclear states with an offer to sign
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) and renouncement to be
recognized as the sixth nuclear weapon power, the Indian Express
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted highly placed diplomats in New Delhi as saying
that India has put forward a third condition to the five permanent
members of the United Nation's Security Council before it signs
the CTBT: economic sanctions imposed on it be removed.
</P>
<P>
The other two conditions put forward by Brajesh Mishra,
Principal Secretary to Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, during
his discussion in European capitals last month, the diplomats
confirmed, are access to dual-use technology and an exemption to
the imposition of fullscope safeguards on India's nuclear
facilities.
</P>
<P>
"India has become very practical now by not asking to be
recognized as a nuclear weapon state," the diplomats said,
implying that this crucial concession had been responsible for
bettering the atmospherics with the P-5.
</P>
<P>
"What India was saying the early days after it tested, that the
nuclear-five had now become the nuclear-six is no longer true.
India is saying it doesn't want to do that now," the diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
One view in diplomatic circles here is that India will be ready
to sign the CTBT "by the winter", thereby paving the way for a
visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton to the country.
</P>
<P>
That is why the scheduled meeting between Jaswant Singh, deputy
chairman of India's Planning Commission and a key aide to
Vajpayee, and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott in
Frankfurt Thursday would be "crucial, but very tough".
</P>
<P>
The encounter would signal how the rest of the negotiations
between India and the P-5 unfolds, according to the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Amid contradictory reports on India's position towards CTBT
lately, some intense and complex negotiations are now under way to
cut a deal with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here have indicated that the government's
position on the CTBT is shifting from criticism toward
consideration of joining if certain concessions in technology
transfer are secured.
</P>
<P>
However, official sources said Sunday that there was no change
in India's basic position on what they called the discriminatory
nature of the CTBT. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's 1st Lady Launches UNICEF's Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nearly four in five Zimbabwean
infants have been vaccinated against the major child-killing
diseases, First Lady Grace Mugabe said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during the launch of United Nations Children's Fund
UNICEF's 1998 Progress of Nations report in Harare, Mrs. Mugabe
said that at independence the ratio had been one in 10 infants
who were vaccinated, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The diseases are measles, tetanus, whooping cough,
tuberculosis, polio and diphtheria.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe can and should still do better," said Mrs. Mugabe,
adding that "we should not be satisfied until all children are
vaccinated against the killer diseases."
</P>
<P>
She said: "We must work hard to maintain and expand basic
immunization levels because every child has a right to be
protected from the vaccine-preventable diseases."
</P>
<P>
A way should be found to include vaccines in the basic
immunization package which treat diseases like hepatitis B, said
Mrs. Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The first lady said this year's Progress of Nations report
focuses on four themes which include child immunization,
adolescence birth registration and homelessness.
</P>
<P>
The report, she said, is an appropriate reminder to everyone
of their responsibility toward children.
</P>
<P>
She said that out of the 12.5 million Zimbabweans, about three
million are children between the ages of 10 and 19.
</P>
<P>
One in five girls aged from 15 to 19 years is either married
or cohabiting, almost always with an older man who has more power
in making decisions, Mrs. Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
She added that one in 10 births in Zimbabwe is to a teenage
mother.
</P>
<P>
The first lady noted that the AIDS scourge is a serious
problem for the youth aged between 15 and 24 years globally,
accounting for more than 50 percent of new HIV infections. And
teenage girls face the greatest risk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
