<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe on Top List of Immunization: UN Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) representative in Harare Justin Maeda said Wednesday
that Zimbabwe has the fourth best record in the world on measles
immunization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of this year's the "Progress of
Nations" report, Maeda described the record as a reasonable proxy
for immunization in general.
</P>
<P>
A total of 40 sub-Sahara African countries were examined by
this report.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe managed to bring child immunization against the six
vaccine-preventable diseases from 10 percent at independence in
1980 to about 80 percent today.
</P>
<P>
The diseases are measles, tetanus, whooping cough,
tuberculosis, polio and diphtheria.
</P>
<P>
Maeda said this was a legacy the country could be proud of
although the struggle is not yet over.
</P>
<P>
"A total of 500,000 children are born in Zimbabwe every year,
and this new generation of children must also be immunized," the
U.N. official added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "we need to make special efforts" to reach the
goal that the great majority of the new born infants are
immunized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
