<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Pakistan Urge Efforts to Solve Afghan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Pakistan on Wednesday
urged intensified cooperation among the United Nations, the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) and regional
countries to solve the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two countries issued the appeal during a meeting here
between Pakistan's special envoy on Afghan affairs Iftekhar
Murshid and his Iranian counterpart Alaeddin Boroujerdi.
</P>
<P>
Murshid said the resolution of the Afghan crisis required
serious cooperation among Afghanistan's neighbors, such as
Pakistan and Iran which are major players in the peace-making
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Murshid, who arrived here Wednesday morning, expressed
Islamabad's satisfaction with its cooperation with Iran on finding
a solution to the Afghan crisis, including the recent dispatch of
joint delegations to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He noted that besides the efforts by Pakistan and Iran, the
U.N., the OIC and other regional countries are also actively
seeking a solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the Afghan peace would not materialize without
the determination by Afghan leaders to make peace.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Boroujerdi cautioned that the road to Afghan peace
was "rocky and harsh" and intensified international efforts were
needed to solve the issue.
</P>
<P>
He voiced Iran's deep concern about the increasing drug
production in the war-torn Afghanistan due to long years of civil
war. He said Iran believed that the war against drug should be
fought in parallel with the peace-making efforts exerted by the
U.N., the OIC and other countries.
</P>
<P>
A civil war has erupted in Afghanistan since former Soviet
Union's army pulled out the country in early 1989. In 1992, the
alliance of guerrilla forces led by Burhanuddin Rabbani captured
the capital of Kabul following years of war with then
Soviet-backed regime.
</P>
<P>
But a new civil war ensued between the Rabbani-led government
and the pro-Islamic Taliban forces, which in September 1996 took
over Kabul and ousted the Rabbani government.
</P>
<P>
Iran, which reportedly supported the deposed Rabbani government,
hosted the first Afghan Peace Conference in January 1997, which
was attended by all Afghan factions except the Taliban. Pakistan,
which reportedly supported the Taliban, boycotted the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, under the mediation of the U.S., the
U.N. and the OIC, Taliban and its rival Northern Alliance held the
first face-to-face peace talks in Pakistan. But the peace talks
quickly broke down due to huge differences between the two sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0020 </DOCNO>
