<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Pleased With Hungary's Reforms, Preparations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Hungary has largely resisted
protectionist pressures to move ahead with major macroeconomic and
structural adjustment in its transition to a market economy, said
the World Trade Organization (WTO) here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Even in the face of large twin fiscal and trade deficits in
1995 and high levels of government debt (internal and external),
the WTO said, Hungary has pursued new trade opportunities,
especially with the European Union (EU), the European Free Trade
Association and partners in the Central European Free Trade
Agreement (CEFTA).
</P>
<P>
"Hungary's preparations for accession to the EU will lead to
more structural and institutional adjustment," said the WTO
report. "Some of the reforms, particularly in the areas of
intellectual property rights and competition policy, go beyond
Hungary's WTO obligations."
</P>
<P>
Based on the WTO secretariat's report and a policy statement by
the Hungarian government, WTO members met on July 7-8 to examine
Hungary's trade policies.
</P>
<P>
The WTO report said that the most dramatic feature of Hungary's
structural adjustment has been the re-orientation of its trade
towards the EU and CEFTA members.
</P>
<P>
The Europe agreement removed most tariff and quantitative
restrictions on trade between Hungary and the EU, with the
exception of agricultural products, textiles and steel.
</P>
<P>
The WTO said that average tariffs remain relatively high for
imports of agricultural products and prepared food, textiles,
clothing and footwear, and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's imports rose from nearly 34 percent of GDP in 1991 to
41 percent in 1996, while exports increased from almost 33 percent
of GDP to about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment (FDI) in 1997 amounted to 2 billion
U.S. dollars, or nearly 5 percent of GDP. Since 1990, Hungary has
attracted 18 billion dollars and now FDI accounts for roughly 40
percent of the total investment stock in Central and Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The WTO said that foreign investors have been attracted to
Hungary mainly because of its skilled labor force, relatively low
wage costs and growing orientation towards European markets.
</P>
<P>
The WTO report concluded that Hungary will face new trade
policy challenges as it intensifies its efforts to join the EU
while still participating in the WTO and engaging in regional
trade agreements with other CEFTA member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Mbeki to Visit Nigeria After Abiola's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki is to visit Nigeria Thursday after the
death of detained Nigerian opposition leader Moshood Abiola, the
government said in a statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the South African government had
learned with great shock and sadness of Abiola's untimely death.
</P>
<P>
"The government is conscious of the fact that this completely
unexpected news has created a very complicated situation for the
government and people of Nigeria," it said.
</P>
<P>
"This is particularly so in the light of the courageous steps
that the new head of state, General Abdulsalam Abubakar, had
taken to advance the process toward Nigeria's return to
democracy," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Accordingly, the governments of the two countries have been
in urgent contact to address this new and grave situation."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the South African government was reassured
that the Nigerian government will take all necessary steps to
assure the Nigerian people and the international community of its
determination to promote the process of genuine democratization.
</P>
<P>
South Africa also appealed to the Nigerian people to respond
to the death of Abiola with restraint.
</P>
<P>
The statement said South Africa decided to mourn Abiola by
flying its national flag at half mast for seven days from July 9
to 15 at the Union Buildings in Pretoria, the seat of government.
</P>
<P>
It said that the move was taken as a token of the deep respect
of the South African government and its people for Abiola and as
an expression of its solidarity with the people of Nigeria at
this critical moment.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, as earlier agreed with the Nigerian
government, Mbeki Thursday would visit Nigeria where he would
also convey the condolences of the president, the government and
people of South Africa to the bereaved family.
</P>
<P>
The relations between South Africa and Nigeria have been
strained since 1995 when South African President Nelson Mandela
led the call for sanctions against the west African country
following the execution of activist Ken Saro Wiwa and a number of
other political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Abiola died in custody Monday shortly before he was expected
to be released along with other political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, who was believed to have won the 1993 presidential
election, was detained after late General Sani Abacha declared
the results of the election invalid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
