<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Leftwing Coalition Divided Over Fortune </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The French leftwing coalition is
divided over the reform of France's fortune tax, or ISF, as the
Communist Party has asked Prime Minister Lionel Jospin not to
yield to the pressure of the employers.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party has proposed extending the ISF to
professional properties, also called "labor tools," which cover
nearly all private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The ISF is the abbreviation for Tax of Solidarity on Fortune.
But French employers said such a measure would harm France's
already heavily-taxed private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Monde said that the Socialist-led government is
expected not to extend the ISF to professional properties and has
made the promise to the country's employers' group, the CNPF.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jospin also has hinted that he would not extend
the ISF to professional properties because France was experiencing
a period of economic growth and needed investment.
</P>
<P>
But the government is considering other measures, including
extending the tax to owners of art objects and forests, to
increase the income from the ISF to 15 billion francs (2.466
billion U.S. dollars) each year instead of the present 10 billion
francs (1.644 billion dollars), said Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued Wednesday, Communist Party National
Secretary Robert Hue called on Jospin not to yield to the pressure
of the CNPF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
