<HEADLINE> Ugandan Vehicles to Get New Plates: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- New plates will be installed to
all vehicles plying within the borders of Uganda and public
service vans will have special marks for identification, a
minister said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
John Nasasira, minister of works, housing and communication,
announced the changes at a function held at the Grand Imperial
Hotel here, Uganda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The new changes are designed in order to identify thieves,
discourage molesting of passengers and to maximize revenue
collection, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The report said all vehicles will have their owners
identification numbers and the new regulations require vehicles
to be registered in one of the eight categories: central
government, local government and municipalities, private,
diplomatic, statutory corporations, duty free/tax exempt,
personalized and dealers plate.
</P>
<P>
Each of the eight categories will have a unique registration
plate with different background colors for the initials/letters
and a different arrangement of digits.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said there will be additional special round
plates for official vehicles of the vice president, the speaker,
the chief justice, the prime minister, cabinet ministers and some
of the members of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The new number plates will run concurrently with the old ones,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Taxis in Kampala had been ordered to have special marks
painted on the sides of the car for easy identification. This
time, they are ordered to put up special roof signs by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The special marks on taxis had been protested by some of the
taxi owners who said the marks affect their business, while the
authorities said the marks are for the sake of management and
security of passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
