<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contact Group Urges Immediate Cease-Fire in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Members of the six-nation Contact
Group Wednesday called for an immediate cease-fire in Kosovo to
pave the way for continuous dialogue on the future status of the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a meeting in Bonn which was held at
political-director level, the group said they would pursue the
cease-fire through immediate talks with both Belgrade and the
Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to seek a resolution of the U.N. Security
Council to press for this demand and others made by them,
including the call for safety guarantee for international
observers operating in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Should the required steps not be taken, the Contact Group would
consider further action under the United Nations Charter,
including military options, to bring about compliance by those who
block the process, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Contact Group, comprising Britain, France,
Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States, also agreed to
recommend "basic elements" for a resolution of the question of
future status of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which is said to be an initiative of Germany and
France, would be worked out to suggest what sort of autonomy
Kosovo should enjoy and would be presented in a secret paper to
Belgrade and leaders of Kosovo Albanians, German Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel told a news conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the population in
the Serbian province of Kosovo, are seeking independence from
Belgrade which stripped Kosovo of its autonomy in 1991. Hundreds
of people have died since last February, when armed conflicts
escalated tensions there into a crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group reiterated Wednesday that it supported
neither the maintenance of the status quo in Kosovo nor the Kosovo
Albanians' claims for independence.
</P>
<P>
However, a deep worry was clearly reflected in the group's
statement about the rising influence of the Kosovo Liberation Army
(KLA), a loosely-structured ethnic Albanian rebel group which is
fighting for Kosovo's independence.
</P>
<P>
"Whether we like or not, the KLA is now a factor on the ground,
apparently controlling at least 30 percent of the territory of
Kosovo. Therefore, it is our view that they have to be taken into
account either directly or indirectly," said U.S. envoy Richard
Gelbard at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
He also noted Washington was trying to involve KLA leaders in
the Kosovo peace process. "If they do not cooperate in the
process, it would be necessary to try to interrupt their ability
to sustain themselves through the full chain of supply," Gelbard
said.
</P>
<P>
Similar view was also voiced in the Contact Group statement,
which stressed that the Kosovo Albanian team to peace dialogues
must be fully representative of their community in order to speak
authoritatively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement requested all countries to prevent the
supply of financial support, weapons or training for armed Kosovo
Albanian groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
