<HEADLINE> Khatami Phones Arafat to Show Support for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Wednesday phoned Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to condemn
Israel's policy of judaizing Jerusalem and reiterate Tehran's
support for the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
Khatami reaffirmed that Iran would continue its "unequivocal"
support for the Palestinian nation and their fight to establish
Jerusalem as its eternal capital, the official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader wished the Palestinians success in their
struggles against Israel through the support of hundreds of
millions of Muslims worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Undersoring the importance of Islamic solidarity in solving the
Palestinian problem, Khatami renewed his call on the Organization
of the Islamic Conference (OIC) to hold an meeting of foreign
ministers to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Arafat thanked Khatami for his efforts in
proposing the convention of OIC foreign ministers to address the
ministers to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
On June 23, Khatami first called for holding a special meeting
of OIC foreign ministers to adopt a united stand against the
recent Israeli decision to expand the municipal boundaries of the
disputed holy city of Jerusalem by annexing several settlements in
the Palestinian territories of West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Soon after Israel approved the plan on June 21, Iran condemned
the decision as a measure to judaize Jerusalem, which is holy to
Muslims, Christians and Jews alike.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's phone call was made following the United Nations
General Assembly voted overwhelmingly Tuesday to upgrade the U.N.
status of the Palestine Liberation Organization from an observer
to that of virtual statehood. 
</P>
