<HEADLINE> Ethiopian PM Meets OAU Ambassadors on Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi Wednesday held talks here with the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) ambassadors committee on the country's border dispute
with neighboring Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry said that in an
explanation that lasted for three and a half hours, Meles gave
"detailed and comprehensive" account of the genesis of the crisis
and relations between Ethiopia and Eritrea since 1991 when
Eritrea won its independence.
</P>
<P>
Meles said: "This country wishes to peacefully settle the crisis."
the Ethiopian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said, contrary to the claim by the Eritrean government, the
cause for the stand off between the two countries is not a
question of border demarcation and delimitation but that of an
invasion by the government in Asmara.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors committee was set up with a fact finding
mission immediately after the peace initiative by the presidents
of Burkina Faso, Zimbabwe and Rwanda and the foreign minister of
Djibouti who shuttled between Addis Ababa and Asmara in June.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda announced last week to pull out of the ambassadors
committee.
</P>
<P>
The committee, chaired by Burkinese ambassador to Ethiopia,
has been to Asmara and will present a report to African leaders.
</P>
<P>
The border dispute between the two Horn of Africa countries
centered on a 400-square-kilometer triangle of rocky land which
both countries claim. The dispute turned violent early in May
when either side accused the other of invasion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
