<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Foreign Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Wednesday called for foreign
assistance to enable it to achieve sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Deputy Finance Minister Godfrey Simasiku made the
appeal at the Zambia-Netherlands annual consultative meeting held
here.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia will not achieve a sustainable development with
the heavy debt burden, which now stands at seven billion U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sustainable growth and poverty reduction can only be achieved
in Zambia with a manageable debt burden, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's currency, Kwacha, depreciated dramatically in the
past several months due to the poor performance of the country's
mining industry and declining balance of payment support from
donors, said Simasiku.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands Ambassador to Zambia Karel de Beer called for
partnership between his country and Zambia in trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
He said people in the Netherlands are willing to invest in
Zambia, depending on the way the Zambian economy moves forward.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that the Netherlands is impressed with
Zambia's economic policies and pledged its continued assistance
to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate of Zambia has risen to 25.7 percent compared
with the annual 18.6 percent of last year.
</P>
<P>
The projected inflation rate of nine percent for this year has
suffered a setback with the high inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the country's currency has continued to
be low with Kwacha now standing at 1,952 against the U.S. Dollar
compared with 1,200 against the Dollar at the beginning of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Germany said last month it will not release its aid to Zambia
as it pledged until the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM)
is privatized.
</P>
<P>
In May the donors pledged Zambia an aid of 530 million
Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
