<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Opens 5th Century Church to Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Queen Noor Wednesday
inaugurated the Petra Church which dated back to the 5th century,
in the ancient Nabataean city of Petra, some 262 kilometers
southwest of Amman.
</P>
<P>
The Petra city was used as a temporary fortress by some
nomadic Nabataean Arabs more than 2,000 years ago. Nabataean is
another name for the Bedouins who are an important part of the
Arabic people.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency quoted an archaeologist from the
United States as saying that the church was converted from a house
in the 5th century, some two centuries younger than the oldest
church in the world which is now widely believed to be at the
Dura-Europas area in Syria.
</P>
<P>
"Style and quality of the temple's elaborate floral friezes
and acanthus-laden limestone capitals suggest that the sanctuary
was constructed (as a house) by the end of the 1st century BC by
the Nabataeans and was (changed into church in the 5th century and
still) in use until the late Byzantine period," said Martha Sharp
Joukowsky from the Brown University in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Other ancient materials found in the building contain a rich
cache of papyrus scrolls, a beautiful mosaic pavement and a
baptistery.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 152 papyrus scrolls were uncovered at the site in
1993. The scrolls constitute the largest group of written
material of antiquities ever found in Jordan. They are currently
being deciphered and have yielded a wealth of information
concerning the Byzantine period in this area, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The church's mosaic pavement includes depictions of native,
exotic animals as well as panels containing personifications of
four seasons, ocean and earth.
</P>
<P>
The church's baptistery, which was constructed in the middle
5th century, is also one of the largest and best preserved
baptisteries in the Near East region, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) began to
sponsor the excavation project of the Petra Church in October 1991
with an injection of 1 million U.S. dollars for the Jordanian
Ministry of Tourism and Antiquities. The ministry then trusted a
group of archaeologists from the Brown University with the job and
they started the excavation in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the Petra Church excavation project is to
enhance tourism in the Petra city, which is one of the most
popular sightseeing venues in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
