<HEADLINE> 15 Puerto Rican Students Arrested During General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Some 15 Puerto Rican students
were arrested early Wednesday as they ran through city streets,
shattering shop windows during a general strike against the sale
of the island telephone company.
</P>
<P>
About 500,000 workers, half of Puerto Rico's workforce, began
to strike on Tuesday in protesting Governor Pedro Rossello's 1.75
billion U.S. dollars deal to sell the state-owned Puerto Rico
Telephone Co. to a consortium led by U.S.-based GTE Corp, reports
from San Juan said.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of people rallied, singing, chanting and
waving the Puerto Rican flag. The strikers also tried to block
traffic in key areas. But they said they had no ties to the
arrested students.
</P>
<P>
Protesters tried to block workers from entering an Eli Lilly
and Co. pharmaceutical manufacturing plant in the eastern San Juan
suburb of Carolina early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Strikers also blocked the entrance to Isla Grande Airport in
San Juan and set up barricades to try to block the entrance to the
Minillas center, a complex in central San Juan that is home to
several government agencies.
</P>
<P>
The telephone company sale is the centerpiece of a
privatization program by Rossello. The phone company lost its
monopoly on local telephone service with the passage of the 1996
Telecommunications Act and cannot compete with the private sector.
</P>
<P>
But the company's 6,000 workers, who began strike on June 18,
said the sale would endanger their jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
