<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Exploring Possibility of No-fly Zone over Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
discussing with Cyprus the possibility of creating a "no-fly"
zone over the divided island as a way to reduce tensions between
the Greek and Turkish communities, U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The no-fly zone is one possibility that could be explored
but we have not made any determination on what the results
should be in terms of how we achieve this reduction in
tensions," Cohen told a joint news conference with visiting
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos.
</P>
<P>
He said the creation of a no-fly zone was one of various
mechanisms that he had discussed with his Greek counterpart
Tsohatzopoulos to reduce tensions between Greek Cypriots and
Turkish Cypriots, who have lived apart sine 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island after a
Greece-backed coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The two parties have recently scrambled for control of the
island's air space and the Greek Cypriot government has planned
to deploy the Russian-built S-300 ground-to-air missiles with a
range of 145 km.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he believed it would be "a mistake" for the Greek
Cypriots to deploy the S-300 air defense system, adding "that
would only add to tensions, rather than decrease them."
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos told the joint news conference that the
Greek Cypriot government had proposed demilitarizing the island,
including a phased Turkish withdrawal. If Turkey agreed,
"possibly one could envisage the non-installation of the S-300
system," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said if Turkey refused to accept a no-fly zone as part of
even a partial demilitarization, "it's very, very difficult for
the Cypriot government thereby to unilaterally move to
disarmament."
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot government has planned to deploy the S-300
air defense system this Summer, but has postponed the delivery
from Russia until November, so that there would be more time for
a solution of the tensions.
</P>
<P>
The proposed no-fly zone is designed to deny control of
Byprus's air space to both Greece and Turkey without
introduction of the S-300 system.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which favors the idea of a no-fly zone, proposed that
NATO or the United Nations provide guarantees for some form of
radar or other monitoring to keep Turkish warplanes from
achieving air superiority.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
