<HEADLINE> U.S., Greece Urge Peaceful Solution for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen and his Greek counterpart Akis Tsohatzopoulos Wednesday
urged a diplomatic rather than military solution to the crisis in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We think a diplomatic solution is the only viable solution for
the long-term stability of the region," Cohen said at a news
conference after meeting Tsohatzopoulos.
</P>
<P>
"We think a military option is the very last option," Cohen
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cohen and Tsohatzopoulos met in Washington as diplomats from
six countries held talks in Bonn, Germany, to discuss efforts to
resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), which
has threatened military intervention in Kosovo, agreed that they
would review a series of military options of "what might be
required in the most extreme case," said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that any action taken by NATO should not be
construed as lending either "moral or military support" for those
ethnic Albanians who are seeking independence.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos said his country does not support the principle
that minorities "in the name of human rights, through violent
action, dissolve existing borders or call into question existing
borders."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two defense ministers also discussed several
options that might be explored to reduce tensions on the divided
island of Greece, including enforcing a no-fly zone over Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, Cohen indicated that they "have not made any
determination on what the results should be in terms of how we
achieve this reduction in tensions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
