<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDZ Drug Could Slow Hepatitis Virus Damage of Liver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A standard AIDZ drug 3TC
appears to slow liver damage caused by hepatitis B, according to
a study in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
The study, by the University of Hong Kong and involving 358
patients, found that after a year of treatment, signs of
inflammatory injury fell significantly in just over half of
those getting the medicine, compared with one-quarter of those
on dummy medication.
</P>
<P>
The drug, manufactured by Glaxo Wellcome and also known as
Lamivudine or Epivir, is one of several that block production of
an essential viral protein known as reverse transcriptase. Both
the AIDZ virus and hepatitis B use this enzyme.
</P>
<P>
The only established treatment, currently is interferon
alpha, which can cause flu-like side effects, but 3TC is easier
to take and may work better.
</P>
<P>
However a scientist from the University of Tokyo noted that
one year of treatment is sufficient enough to suggest that this
drug is effective, further study is needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
