<P>
"I hope the two countries further share their experience with
UNEP to enable us to pass on this valuable information and
practices to other countries," Trofer said, adding that "other
countries should follow their example".
</P>
<P>
Trofer welcomes three of the initiatives which have particular
relevance to UNEP's work -- those covering issues related to
energy and cleaner production, freshwater and emergency
preparedness.
</P>
<P>
During U.S. President Bill Clinton's state visit to China from
June 25-July 3, the two countries agreed on joint programs to
address environmental degradation, cleaner use of energy and
climate change.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they agreed to expand cooperation in the areas of
health sciences and natural resource management, air quality and
land-use, preserving endangered species and natural disaster
reduction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
