<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's shortage of potable water is expected to
reach about 107 million cubic meters, sources at the Jordanian
Ministry of Water and Irrigation said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic-language daily Alam Al Yom reported Thursday that
Jordan actually needs 388 million cubic meters of potable water
while only 281 million cubic meters are available.
</P>
<P>
The paper added deficit of water for industrial purposes will
reach some 16 million cubic meters by the year 2000 when the
actual needs are estimated at 58 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Defense expenditures of the Gulf states constitute
a heavy burden on their budgets which largely depend on petroleum
exports, obstructing their economic development.
</P>
<P>
Economic and military experts were quoted as saying that member
states of the Gulf Cooperation Council have spent over 150 billion
U.S. dollars on defense since the 1990 Gulf crisis set off by
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The elite predicted that defense expenditures will remain high
in the coming years due to the instability in the region, which
has prompted an arms race.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Palestinian undersecretary of state for labor,
Hisham Antabawi, said that all arrangements were finalized for the
signing of an agreement with the international rehabilitation
center to dispatch 8,000 Palestinians to work in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- Palestinians working in Israel so far this year
have risen to 55,000 from last year's 48,000, a survey released
Wednesday by the Palestinian Central Statistics Department said.
</P>
<P>
The number of those working in Israel this year accounted for
20.5 percent of Palestine's total labor force, up 4.4 percentage
points from last year, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The survey said Palestinian workers are mainly engaged in
agriculture, mining, trade, services and construction.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Exports of Egypt's free trade zone have risen to 194
million dollars in the first six months of this year, with exports
to American markets increasing by 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic-language newspaper Al Akhbar said Thursday the
exports of the free zone in June increased by 14 percent as
compared with the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt is aiming to produce an average of 830,000
barrels per day of crude oil in the 1998-1999 fiscal year starting
July as output from mature fields is supplemented by new
discoveries, the Egyptian Gazette reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Oil ministry officials said that an initial daily output target
of 850,000 was lowered in line with a policy of reservoir
management or maintenance.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian economy grew by 5.3-5.4 percent in the
1997-1998 fiscal year ending June, failing to meet the 5.7 percent
target, the Egyptian Gazette reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But Economy Minister Youssef Boutros-Ghali said Wednesday that
earnings from tourism, which made up 4 percent of the gross
domestic product and 7 percent if economic activities indirectly
linked to it were taken into account, proved more "resilient" than
expected, with hotel occupancy has been now back to an average of
60 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
