<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Urges International Financial Institutions to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday urged the
international financial institutions to activate their program and
project financing as it has met all its commitments with the
multilateral financial agencies.
</P>
<P>
The international financial institutions should honor their
commitments for program and project financing, irrespective of the
sanctions as the Pakistani government has met all its commitments
as per the program and its discussions with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) mission in may 1998.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz made these remarks Thursday during
a joint press conference with IMF director Paul Chabrier, who is
here as head of an IMF fact-finding mission after the sanctions
against Pakistan for its detonation of nuclear devices at the end
of May.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the IMF mission has come to consult with the
Pakistani government on the emerging scenario following the
imposition of sanctions and to determine the extent to which the
projections of balance of payments for 1998-99 fiscal year had
changed in light of these developments.
</P>
<P>
The government has informed the IMF mission that despite the
difficulties experienced more recently in June, and due to the
lack of programmed inflows, "we have met all the key quantitative
performance targets for end of the fiscal year 1997-98, except
that of foreign exchange reserves," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He said the mission has completed its analysis of the outlook
for the balance of payments on a monthly and quarterly basis for
1998-99 in the presence of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, however, said that due to lack of inflow of new program
assistance and the negative impact on private sector inflows, the
balance of payments position is expected to deteriorate
significantly in relation to the projections made in May by the
IMF mission.
</P>
<P>
"The government has strongly emphasized that this deterioration
is not due to any change in underlying fundamentals of the economy
which had, in fact, improved substantially in 1997-98, but due
primarily to 'exogenous'," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that suspension of inflow from the IMF as part of
the ESAF/EFF (Extended Structural Adjustment Facility/Extended
Fund Facility) will affect the balance of payments both directly
and indirectly as other multilateral agencies like the World Bank
and the Asian Development Bank have also linked their support to
the resumption of the program.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission met with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Wednesday
in Lahore. They were informed of the circumstances that forced
Pakistan to conduct the nuclear blasts following the nuclear tests
by India which altered the balance of power in the region and
created a deep sense of insecurity in the Pakistani people.
</P>
<P>
According to Aziz, Sharif emphasized that "since Pakistan had
more than successfully implemented the program, it would only be
fair for donors to continue with the program."
</P>
<P>
Sharif noted that Pakistan acted in response to the action by
India and it was wrong that sanctions should be uniformly applied
on both countries which are likely to have an even greater adverse
impact on Pakistan in the short run.
</P>
<P>
According to Aziz, Sharif has written letters to heads of the
G-7 countries highlighting these concerns and emphasizing the need
for immediate restoration of support from the international
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the IMF mission led by Paul Chabrier has noted
Pakistan's concerns and has assured that it will fully inform the
representatives of the G-7 countries in the IMF Board of the major
financial crisis that is likely to occur in Pakistan due to the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the ESAF/EFF program is activated quickly, Pakistan
will be left with few options," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Chabrier is expected to brief the executive directors of the
G-7 countries next Monday in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Flood Peak Hits Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The southwestern city of
Chongqing has been put on alert against flooding since high water
levels on the Yangtze River hit it early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Water levels were the highest in 6 years, at 181.75 meters,
which was 1.75 meters above the danger line, at about 5:00
a.m. (Beijing time), according to the Hydrology Bureau of the
Upper Reaches of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The flooding was caused by repeated torrential rains on
tributaries of the Yangtze along its upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
Flood control departments in Chongqing mobilized 66,000 people
to fight the flooding, using nearly 300 lifeboats, 660 trucks, and
440,000 sandbags. The municipal government also allocated 5
million yuan (600,000 US dollars) for special flood-relief funds.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
