<HEADLINE> Pak Trade Gap Reduced to 1.53B Dollars in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's trade deficit stood at
1.53 billion U.S. dollars during the fiscal year of 1997-98 as
against that of last year's 3.57 billion dollars, showing an
improvement of 57.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released Thursday by the Commerce
Ministry, Pakistan's exports amounted to 8.52 billion dollars
while imports reached 10.05 billion dollars during the fiscal year
ending on June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The exports showed an increase of 2.5 percent compared with
8.32 billion dollars recorded in the 1996-97 financial year while
the imports decreased by 15.5 percent compared with last year's
11.89 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In June 1998, the country's exports dropped 0.6 percent to 685
million dollars from 689 million dollars in May. The figure of
exports also indicated a decline of 13.5 percent when compared
with exports of 792 million dollars in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Imports during June 1998 totaled 896 million dollars showing an
increase of 29.1 percent when compared with 694 million dollars in
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
However, when compared with 1.17 billion dollars of imports in
June 1997, the imports this June showed a drop of 23.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the financial year of 1997-98, the
Pakistani government set its target of trade deficit at 2.33
billion dollars, indicating a decrease of 970 million dollars as
against 3.3 billion dollars of the previous fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
