<HEADLINE> HK to Make Continued efforts to Tackle Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region has called for sustained, concerted
and collective efforts in tackling unemployment and creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
This message came from the second meeting of the Task Force on
Employment convened here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said after chairing the
meeting that members of the task force are aware that as Hong Kong
is going through a difficult economic adjustment period,
unemployment will remain at a relatively high level for some time.
</P>
<P>
The current unemployment rate in Hong Kong is 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
There are no quick fixes to the problem short of the onset of
an economic recovery, the financial secretary said.
</P>
<P>
The task force members noted that the government had already
been implementing a number of proposals which tally with the major
views expressed such as bringing forward infrastructure projects,
strengthening employment services, improving training and
retraining services, creating jobs to clean up the environment,
and stepping up enforcement efforts against illegal employment,
according to Tsang.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government also informed the meeting that the
Vocational Training Council and the Employees Retraining Board
would launch in September a special seafarers training program for
 the unemployed which comprises 14 weeks' classroom training,
followed by an in-service training program on board a vessel, and
another nine weeks' in-service training.
</P>
<P>
The task force meeting also noted two other job creation areas,
one in a new tourism site and another in major repair and
maintenance works for non-estate aided schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
