<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Visits Flooded Parts Of Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Premier Zhu Rongji visited Hubei
and Hunan provinces over the last four days to have a look at the
flood relief work and preparations there.
</P>
<P>
He was accompanied by Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao, head of the
State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters and went to
Jingzhou in Hubei the morning of July 6 to inspect the banks of
the Jingjiang section of the Yangtze River and dykes near Hubei's
capital, Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
He went to Hunan from Tuesday to today to look at flood control
work on the Yangtze, at Dongting Lake, and in the provincial
capital, Changsha.
</P>
<P>
Extending his thanks to the people involved in the flood-relief
struggle, Zhu said that the flood control work has reached a
crucial stage. The work is of great significance to the country as
whether it can attain the goals in economic growth and ensure
smooth progress in its reforms, he said.
</P>
<P>
Steps should be taken to prepare for even bigger floods in
northern China, and in coastal areas, preparations should be made
to guard against typhoons, he said.
</P>
<P>
Water resources should be strengthened, with special attention
given to the flood water capacity of large rivers and the ecology
of the upper reaches of major rivers, he said. 
</P>
