<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Agrees to Clean Up Toxic Wastes in Former Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States has reportedly
agreed to act and clean up the alleged toxic wastes its military
has left in the former bases in the Philippines, the official
Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A ranking official of the Philippine Department of Foreign
Affairs was quoted as saying the U.S. will shortly hire private
American companies with technical capabilities in toxic wastes
management to undertake the clean-up.
</P>
<P>
Focus of the toxic wastes issue involves the former U.S. Naval
Base in Subic, Zambales province, and the former Clark Airbase in
nearby Pampanga province.
</P>
<P>
Both Subic and Clark are now bustling economic zones to which
they have been converted since the U.S. military left in 1991 and
1992 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has never formally admitted it left toxic wastes
dumped in its former military bases in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Militant Filipino non-governmental organizations, however,
insisted the U.S. did and even got the services of two U.S.
environmental firms to undertake studies and determine the
existence of the toxic wastes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. agreement to undertake the clean-up, the foreign
department official said, could have been based on the idea of
showcasing U.S. technology and capability in cleaning up toxic
wastes, and complying with the Rio Declaration calling for
military organizations to leave their abandoned bases as
environmentally friendly as possible.
</P>
<P>
The toxic wastes issue is expected to figure prominently in the
now ongoing annual meeting of the Philippine-U.S. Mutual Defense
Board in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon earlier
admitted the Philippine panel to the talks, which includes him,
will raise the issue during their meetings.
</P>
<P>
The board meeting is likewise expected to discuss updates on
the pending Visiting Forces Agreement signed last year between the
two countries. The Philippine Senate has yet to ratify the
agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
