<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Pakistan Agree to Help Solve Afghan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Pakistan have agreed to
continue efforts and send joint teams to Afghanistan to push
forward the peace process there, Iran's special envoy on Afghan
affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the official news agency IRNA at the end of a visit
by his Pakistani counterpart Iftakhar Murshid to Iran, Boroujerdi
said the teams will assess the situation in the war-torn country
and request the World Health Organization (WHO) and other states
to help.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' representatives to Afghanistan had listened
to views of Afghans in northern and southern parts of the country,
Boroujerdi said. He said that since both the Taliban and the
Northern United Front welcomed the peace efforts, Iran and
Pakistan decided to take further steps in this direction.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamic Taliban regime came to power after its militia
captured the capital Kabul in September 1996, and now controls
most parts of the country. Its first direct talks with the
guerrilla alliance which controls the north broke down in April in
Islamabad due to wide differences.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban is said to be backed by Pakistan while the ousted
government of President Burhanuddin Rabbani retains Iran's support
and recognition.
</P>
<P>
For his part, the Pakistani official said both sides put
emphasis on continued joint efforts to resolve the Afghan crisis,
adding it is a sign of encouragement to see that the warring
factions are interested in restoring a just peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
Murshid said it is in the interests of both Iran and Pakistan,
and is also their common strategy, to bring various Afghan
factions to the negotiating table and forge a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
Terming his talks with Iranians officials "constructive,"
Murshid said that what Iran and Pakistan are doing is not
intervention in affairs of a third country, but rather in harmony
with those of the United Nations and the Organization of the
Islamic Conference.
</P>
<P>
Murshid arrived here Wednesday morning and held talks with
Boroujerdi and Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on
continuing joint efforts to advance the stalled Afghan peace
process. 
