<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Discusses Civil Service Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's heads of ministries
Thursday held a one-day workshop to discuss the framework for the
second phase of the public service reform program (1998-2000) in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
Public Service, Labor and Welfare Minister Florence Chitauro
made a key address on the reform.
</P>
<P>
She said, ''it now remains your duty and function to mobilize
all resources at your disposal and focus on the three reform
components, namely, focusing on core business, ensuring
efficiency and effectiveness throughout the service and capacity
building.''
</P>
<P>
Chitauro said focusing the public service on its core business
was a prerequisite for the reduction of government expenditure.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the second phase of the reforms at least 33,000
civil service posts would have been abolished, she said.
</P>
<P>
the restructuring of the public service started with the
voluntary retirement exercise that ended in 1995 and saw over
23,000 posts abolished.
</P>
<P>
Chitauro said restructuring was ''necessary'' and
''imperative'' as the role of the government in the provision and
delivery of services continued to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are about 170,000 civil service posts in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, ''the restructuring of the public service
and its focus on core business will lead to acceleration of
growth and investment, economic empowerment through
indigenization, reducing levels of unemployment and ensuring
sustainable growth.''
</P>
<P>
She urged the heads of ministries to be conversant with the
objectives of the second phase of the public service reforms so
as to map out the reform process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
