<HEADLINE> Yangtze River's Water Levels to Remain High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Water levels in the middle and
lower reaches of the Yangtze River will remain high for some time
to come because of flooding in the upper reaches, China's State
Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters reports.
</P>
<P>
It says that dyke patrols along the Yangtze River need to be
increased and rescue crews need to be ready for possible breaches.
</P>
<P>
Water in the middle and lower reaches reached warning levels
after torrential rainfall hit southern and eastern China from June
12 on.
</P>
<P>
Almost 2 million people have been mobilized to fight the
flooding, which has not yet caused major damage to the
dykes. Water levels in the middle and upper reaches started going
down a couple of days ago, but the rate is slowing down because of
more flooding in the upper reaches of the Yangtze, which is now
flowing at a rate of 48,600 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Flooding in the upper reaches will not add to the flooding in
the middle and lower reaches now, but it will slow the decline in
floodwaters later, the headquarters says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
