<HEADLINE> China Dealing With Fake Goods And Business Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Wang Zhongfu, director of China's
State Administration for Industry and Commerce (SAIC), China's
market watchdog, says that they are removing fake milk powder and
cosmetics from store shelves and are continuing to fight these
illegal sales across the country.
</P>
<P>
Their market studies are targeting fake goods and business
fraud nationwide, with milk powder, instant drinks, cigarettes,
cosmetics, foodstuff, alcohol, and agriculture materials high on
their list. They are also cracking down on smuggling and
pornography in Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
SAIC has asked local government departments to stop blackmarket
sales and to improve grain market controls by financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
State Councillor Wu Yi has asked administrative departments to
help establish a well-managed market as the country builds a
market economy.
</P>
<P>
Industry and commerce offices have dealt with nearly 900,000
cases of violations of economic laws and regulations since 1994,
involving more than 30 billion yuan (3.6 billion US dollars).
</P>
