<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Policies Passed in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala comfortably won the first battle against his rivals
Thursday when the Lower House of Parliament voted 95-64 for the
programs and policies presented by his government for the 1998/99
fiscal year which begins in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
For the passage of the programs and policies, a simple majority
over the negative votes is needed in the house.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), which helped the government win the
vote of confidence in April, voted against the programs and
policies.
</P>
<P>
It accused the government of failing to solve the problems of
the people at the opening session on June 28 and indicated that it
might withdraw its support.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML), the
second largest opposition in parliament, boycotted the house
session as per the understanding it reached with the ruling Nepali
Congress (NC) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu Post said Thursday that under the understanding,
the CPN-ML should boycott the house proceedings Thursday to clear
the way for the NC government to obtain a majority of votes for
its programs and policies.
</P>
<P>
And the CPN-ML will join the government after the passage of
the budget for the coming fiscal year to be presented to
parliament Friday.
</P>
<P>
Both the CPN-UML and the CPN-ML have criticized the government
programs, saying that they fail to initiate any new measures of
national development.
</P>
<P>
The programs and policies, presented to parliament on July 1
through King Birendra, give priority to human resource development
and poverty eradication by attaining a high rate of economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Koirala resigned on July 10, 1994 after failing to get his
government programs and policies passed in parliament.
</P>
<P>
In reply to queries by MPs prior to the voting, Prime Minister
Koirala said that Nepal's border with India will be systematized
and even one inch of land will not be lost to India.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have been demanding the government to
initiate measures for the immediate withdrawal of Indian army from
Kalapani in far-western Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that he will talk with Bhutanese King Jigme Singye
Wangchuck and Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee over the
refugee issue on the sidelines of the 10th Summit of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) to be held late
this month in Colombo, Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
He said that if India again refuses to mediate in the issue,
his country will internationalize it.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in eastern Nepal
in eight U.N.-run camps after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Seven rounds of ministerial talks between the two Himalayan
kingdoms have failed to produce any result. And India has refused
to get involved in the matter, saying it is a bilateral issue.
</P>
<P>
More grave challenges lie ahead for Koirala as a simple
majority of 103 votes is needed in the 205-seat Lower House for
the passage of the new budget.
</P>
<P>
But there will be no problem if the CPN-ML, which has 40 seats
in the house, throws its weight behind Koirala, whose NC party
holds 88 seats in the house.
</P>
<P>
At press time, the Upper House is still debating on the
policies and programs. But there is no doubt that they will get
passed as the Nepali Congress dominates the Upper House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
