<HEADLINE> Blair Fails to Resolve Orange March Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Talks between British Prime Minister
Tony Blair and senior Northern Ireland Orangemen failed Thursday
to achieve a breakthrough in a tense five-day stand-off in
Portadown, west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Protestant leaders refused to back down from their insistence
that Orange Order members be allowed to parade their traditional
route through a Roman Catholic housing estate in the town.
</P>
<P>
The growing sectarian tension has prompted concern that the
implementation of the April 10 peace pact could be jeopardized as
political aspirations for peace are clouded by the continuing
unrest.
</P>
<P>
Calling it a "very difficult situation", a Downing Street
spokesman, however, said after the meeting that the prime minister
welcomed the efforts of the Orange leaders to "keep the
temperature down".
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister is determined to keep talking and promote a
dialogue in a very difficult situation, but we are not in a
position to reverse the decision," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
For their part, the Orangemen representatives said they would
go back to Northern Ireland and inform their "brethren" of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
The Orangemen said they would keep up their protest near
Garvaghy Road until they were allowed to complete their march
along the route they have used for nearly 200 years.
</P>
<P>
The parade traditionally uses the route of Garvaghy Road area
but was banned this year by the independent Parades Commission,
and the security forces have mounted a massive operation to keep
protesters out, leading to a stand-off with the Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
The stand-off has sparked widespread street violence in
Northern Ireland for the past four nights, especially in Belfast.
Already there have been 437 attacks on police including 12
shootings and 25 bomb attacks.
</P>
<P>
Police has warned people not to travel unless it was
essential. 
</P>
</TEXT>
