<HEADLINE> China Opens More Sectors for Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of the Asian financial
crisis, China has decided to allow foreign businesses to invest
in some sectors that were traditionally restricted like internal
trade and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
China needs to adapt its foreign capital utilization to changes
both inside and outside the country, He Ju, vice-minister of
the State Development Planning Commission's foreign capital
utilization department, told a conference on China's foreign
investment policies for development zones.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will develop measures to encourage
foreign investment in the following areas:
</P>
<P>
- The service sector, which is expected to be a new attraction
to foreign investors in internal trade, tourism, accounting, legal
affairs, air transportation, finance, and telecommunications;
</P>
<P>
- Large and medium-sized state enterprises and private
businesses;
</P>
<P>
- Large state enterprises for investment by multinationals and
Sino-foreign projects involving advanced technology where a larger
market share may be given to foreign partners;
</P>
<P>
- Central and western parts of China are places for more
foreign investment, where the central government's policy is to
give priority to foreign capital especially in backbone industries
and state projects; for restricted projects, the proportion of
foreign ownership can be larger than in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, by the end of May, China had approved 312,174
foreign-funded businesses, with 236.7 billion U.S. dollars worth
of actual foreign investment. Most of the over 100,000
foreign-funded enterprises that have started doing business are in
good shape and showing a profit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
