<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Members Agree to Implement Trade Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The 12th meeting of ministers of
trade and industry of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) has worked out a plan of implementing the trade protocol
among member nations.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting closed in Luanda Wednesday, the
ministers discussed issues concerning the implementation of the
protocol in a bid to facilitate their bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
Under the trade protocol, tariff barriers will be gradually
removed within eight years in SADC so as to increase trade among
its members.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government asked to be granted another four years
of grace for the total removal of tariff barriers on the ground
that it is disadvantaged in trade competitiveness because of the
prolonged civil war in the country.
</P>
<P>
The proposal made by Angola has been agreed upon by the
representatives of other SADC member states.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at the meeting that Angola should, with the
assistance of the SADC Executive Secretariat, look into the
impact of the implementation of the trade protocol upon the
war-ravaged country and submit a list of products qualified for
trade liberalization. Angola can only sign on the protocol when
all these have been done.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that all the SADC members but Angola have
signed on the trade pact.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, it was also agreed that all the member state
should do more to train their own trade personnel and improve
their negotiating skills in the international trade.
</P>
<P>
SADC has 13 members -- Angola, Namibia, Lesotho, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Swaziland, Malawi, South Africa, Zambia, Zimbabwe,
Tanzania, Botswana and the Democratic Republic of Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
