<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Looking for $300M to Build Telecom Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market of Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) is scouting for 300 million U.S. Dollars
to build a telecommunications network that will link all member
states via digital terrestrial network and satellite system.
</P>
<P>
The private liability company to be known as Comtel will be
established with the national telecommunications operators as
shareholders and private sector including institutional investors
on a build-operate-transfer basis, the Times of Zambia paper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The need to invite private sector financiers within and
outside the project countries will help in mobilizing the
required investment funds through either equity or debt
financing, according to a final communique of the recent COMESA
meeting of the Council of Ministers held in late June in
Kinshasa, capital of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The investment initially estimated at 273 million U.S. Dollars
over a period of five years is billed as profitable as it is
expected to raise at least 59 percent internal rate of returns
and net present value of 660 million U.S. Dollars at 10 percent
for the initial five years.
</P>
<P>
In the design of the project, the network will be built on
existing infrastructure through new transmission routes and the
transit centers have been specified for Zambian capital of
Lusaka, Kenyan capital of Nairobi, Ethiopian capital of Addis
Ababa and Johannesburg in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
These centers will be modified to accommodate the volume of
traffic expected as the interconnectivity project will mainly use
the Asynchronous Transfer Mode technology.
</P>
<P>
The realization of Comtel will provide a reliable and
homogeneous network across the region and this will eliminate the
current practice of transmitting through third countries (in most
cases Europe and the United States), resulting in substantial
reduction in communication cost, said the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
