<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Thursday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Nigeria's military ruler agreed to allow outside experts
to take part in the autopsy on the opposition leader Moshood K.
O. Abiola and spoke in vague terms of moving the country toward
democracy. His statements were intended to soothe public anger
after Abiola's sudden death.
</P>
<P>
-- Japan's Prime Minister Hashimoto promised long-term tax cuts
beginning next year, but he gave no details about how the move
might help Japan's sagging economy. Hashimoto's promise seemed
aimed at winning support from Washington and Japanese voters, who
go to the polls on Sunday to choose members of the upper house of
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- In the 100 years since the United States claimed Puerto Rico
as spoils of the Spanish-American War, islanders have wrestled
with the ambiguity of their political status -- adrift between two
cultures, not entirely comfortable with either. Nowhere has this
identity crisis been more starkly drawn than in a general strike
Tuesday and today to protest the sale of the state-owned Puerto
Rico Telephone Co.
</P>
<P>
-- Dow Corning Corp. has agreed to pay 3.2 billion U.S. dollars
to settle claims of about 170,000 women who say their silicone
breast implants made them sick. If the proposed settlement is
approved, individual women could receive from 12,000 dollars to
60,000 dollars apiece. In addition, the company would pay 5,000
dollars to women demanding surgery to remove their implants, and
25,000 dollars to compensate women whose implants had ruptured.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. and five allies demanded an immediate cease-fire
in Kosovo and called on governments to stop the flow of funds to
ethnic Albanian rebels. Meanwhile, Serb forces mounted an offensive
on the Albanian border near the village of Morina, killing six.
Four NATO warships visited Albania's port of Durres in a fresh
show of strength. 
</P>
