<HEADLINE> UNEP Praises Environ. Progress at Sino-U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Nairobi-based United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) Thursday spoke highly of the
achievements made at last week's historic Sino-U.S. summit on the
global environment.
</P>
<P>
"The agreements reached in Beijing should send a positive
signal of environmental cooperation around the world... This is
the direction to go, and other countries should follow their
example," UNEP Executive Director Klaus Topfer told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
China and the U.S. have reached agreements on fighting
environmental degradation, preserving endangered species,
emergency preparedness, fresh water and marine resources
conservation and natural disaster reduction.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also decided to expand cooperation in
the areas of health sciences and natural resources management and
signed special pacts on air quality and land use, said the UNEP
executive director.
</P>
<P>
Many of the programs agreed to by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton "reflect UNEP's new
areas of concentration," said Topfer.
</P>
<P>
He said that UNEP is strengthening its work related to cleaner
production and its capacity to deal with the
environmentally-sound management of fresh water resources.
</P>
<P>
"These two issues are clearly a high priority for China and
the U.S., and also for UNEP," he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNEP boss made the remarks after holding talks with Xia
Kunbao, Chinese Deputy Permanent Representative to UNEP, and U.S.
Permanent Representative Allen Latimer respectively at the UNEP
headquarters here earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
"Combining economic growth with environmental caution is our
main responsibility, and in this regard, UNEP welcomes the
positive steps in this direction announced (in Beijing) last
week," he said.
</P>
<P>
UNEP plays a leading role worldwide in monitoring and
assessing existing and emerging environmental problems, alerting
policy makers and the public and coordinating efforts to tackle
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
