<HEADLINE> Mozambican Minister on Intervention in G. Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- It is too early for Mozambique to
send intervention troops to Guinea Bissau before the
international diplomatic mediation comes to an end, Mozambican
Defense Minister Aguiar Mazula has said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Noticias newspaper quoted the defense minister as
saying that "we are not in position to send a contingent in
response to the call for resolving the regional conflict" because
registration of recruits has just started in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace agreement reached by the parties concerned in
1992, the Mozambican armed forces should have a total number of
30,000 troops. For various reasons, they currently have only
12,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Mazula was referring to the remarks made by Guinean Bissau
President Joao Vieira who blamed Portuguese-speaking countries in
Africa for failure to send troops to intervene in his nation.
</P>
<P>
"It may not be fit for Mozambique to intervene without the
support of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the United
Nations before the efforts by the countries neighboring Guinea
Bissau comes to an end," Mazula said in Maputo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister disclosed that the issue must be
addressed at the summit of the Portuguese-speaking nations to be
held in Cape Verde next week.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the OAU has discussed the Guinea Bissau crisis
and decided that the issue should be resolved through talks by
the nations of that region as the crisis is still within regional
scale.
</P>
<P>
Guinea and Senegal have sent some 2,000 troops to help the
Vieira Government's efforts to end the revolt led by former Army
Chief of Staff Amsumane Mane which broke out a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the pro-government Noticias said in an editorial
Wednesday that it is inappropriate for President Vieira to blame
the five Portuguese-speaking nations in Africa for their failure
to act to end the conflict in the tiny west African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
