<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Starts Listing People to Be Resettled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
started identifying the first batch of people to be resettled
soon on 12 farms now serviced for resettlement while another 14
are in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Land Acquisition Committee Joseph Msika told
the daily Herald paper Wednesday that the process to identify
the people follows a government order last month to chiefs,
head men and provincial administrators.
</P>
<P>
The decree demanded they should immediately start compiling
lists of those who required to be resettled in their areas.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of people identified so far is not
immediately available, about 183 families are expected to be
resettled on the 12 farms, which cover a combined area of 16,035
hectares, Msika said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the ongoing exercise to identify the people
would see more villagers being resettled on 14 other farms that
would soon be ready.
</P>
<P>
The exercise was being speeded up following the invasion of
commercial farms last month by the angry landless peasants bitter
about government's delay in resettling them.
</P>
<P>
These peasants had threatened to grab the farms if they were
not resettled by September.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has frequently said only full-time
skilled farmers will be resettled to ensure that agricultural
production is enhanced.
</P>
<P>
During the first resettlement exercise in the 1980s, the
government was criticized for resettling farmers without skills
on the farms which the villagers could not use fully, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
