<HEADLINE> China's Busy Hotline For Complaints Against Prosecutors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) - A complaint hotline to handle
citizen's complaints about prosecutors that was opened by China's
Supreme People's Procuratorate on May 28 has been receiving over
50 calls a day.
</P>
<P>
China's procurators have been criticised by delegates to the
National People's Congress and the new Procurator-General Han
Zhubin has been making an effort to improve methods at the
thousands of offices, and the hotline to handle the public's
reports of misconduct by prosecutors has been a part of this.
</P>
<P>
According to Yao Shigen, an official at the hotline center,
nearly 600 of the complaints have concerned prosecutors' and
procuratorates' misdeeds like failing to return illegally obtained
assets, seeking personal profit from official duties and detaining
suspects for long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Procuratorate has ordered provincial
procuratorates to respond to each case and to deal with the
problems, Yao says.
</P>
<P>
The other complaints are against law enforcement offices and
administrative agencies and some have given evidence of
corruption, while others have sought advise on legal matters.
</P>
<P>
"All calls will be handled properly and considered for further
investigation by related departments," Yao promises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
