<HEADLINE> EU Needs Stronger Anti-Hooligan Measures in Euro 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- European Union countries should take
stronger measure to curb the spread of hooliganism in the two years
leading to the European championship in 2000, a FIFA security
specialist said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely true that we may face the same problems as here
in France," said Horst Schmidt of Germany, who is in charge of
security in FIFA's World Cup organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
"European Union should be involved in this matter more than ever in
the past, not only in ticketing affairs, but also in security
affairs," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We have to find new solutions, new ways of co-operation," Schmidt
told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The European championship in 2000 will be co-hosted by the
Netherlands and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Two months ago, European Union had exerted pressures on the French
World Cup Organizing Committee, forcing the latter to open ticket sale
hotlines for distribution of match tickets.
</P>
<P>
Schmidt, who has years of experiences in the security relating to
soccer, said there is a tendency of the internationalization of the
hooliganism.
</P>
<P>
"Looking into future, I believe hooliganism will become an
international movement. I have signals that hooligans try to organize
themselves not only on a national basis," said Schimidt.
</P>
<P>
But he said the riots in Marseille and in Lens had totally
different origins.
</P>
<P>
In Marseille the ticketless English fans rioted against rival
supporters while in Lens, it was the neo-Nazist German hooligans
taking on the French police, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These German hooligans have nothing to do with football," said
Schmidt, who was also General Secretary of the German Football
Federation.
</P>
<P>
"In the past ten years we have tried to fight this problem but
without success," he said.
</P>
<P>
French gendarme was beaten into coma by iron bar-wielding German
hooligans in Lens on June 21.
</P>
<P>
Schmidt insisted despite these troubles security in the stada was
generally good. 
</P>
</TEXT>
