<HEADLINE> Chinese Television to Carry Live Coverage Of Civil Lawsuits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China Central Television (CCTV)
plans to begin broadcasting live coverage of civil lawsuits on
July 11 with a court case involving a suit over an alleged film
copyright violation.
</P>
<P>
It will be broadcast Saturday morning from Beijing's No.1
Intermediate People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Ten major Chinese film studios are suing the Beijing Tiandu
Film Copyright Agency Center, the Tianjin Taida Audio and Video
Distribution Center, and the Zhongying Audio and Visual Publishing
House for 27 instances of copyright violation.
</P>
<P>
The open trial is considered a basic part of China's legal
system and citizens are allowed to be present at cases that do not
involve confidential state matters and certain other cases.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court became the first
intermediate court in China to allow Chinese citizens 18 or older
to be present at open trials when it began the practice on June 10.
</P>
<P>
CCTV will invite experts and scholars to its studio to discuss
laws on intellectual property rights protection with the audience
and to answer their questions.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the broadcast will help increase people's
awareness of the law and and will put the nation's courts under
greater media scrutiny. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
