<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks' Non-performing Loans Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The non-performing loans or past due
accounts of commercial banks in the Philippines continued to rise
from 7.6 percent in March this year to 8.8 percent as of April 30,
the central bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the banks' non-performing loans level is
still at single digit and has only risen due to the central bank's
tighter definition of past due accounts.
</P>
<P>
The central bank reported that as of April this year, total
loans stood at 1.535 trillion pesos (38.4 billion U.S. dollars),
up 0.72 percent from the March level of 1.524 trillion pesos (38.1
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans alone rose 16.7 percent to 134.9 billion
pesos (3.4 billion dollars) as of April this eyar from only 115.6
billion pesos (2.9 billion dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
The non-performing loans accounted for 8.8 percent of the
banks' total loans as of end-April.
</P>
<P>
The commercial banks' reserves for probable loan losses
amounted to 41 billion pesos (1 billion dollars) as of April this
year, equivalent to 2.7 percent of total loan portfolio, the
central bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
