<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, Thailand Sign Extradition Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and Thailand signed here
Thursday an extradition treaty to enable the handover of criminals
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was signed by Bangladeshi State Minister for Foreign
Affairs Abul Hasan Chowdhury and Thai Deputy Foreign Minister
Sukhumbhand Paribatra, who arrived here Wednesday on a three-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
This is the first treaty of its kind this South Asian nation
has signed with a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, Thailand would extradite Major Bazlul Huda,
one of the accused in the murder case of Sheikh Mujib Rahman --
Bangladesh's first prime minister after independence in 1971, who
was assassinated in 1975. Huda has been detained in a Thai jail.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the treaty was a "historic event," said
Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad. "We would look
forward" to further cooperation with Thailand in other fields for
mutual benefit, he added.
</P>
<P>
For his part, the Thai deputy foreign minister said, "This is
the beginning of cooperation between Thailand and Bangladesh in
combating certain criminal activities like narcotics and child
prostitution."
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi would try to negotiate similar treaties with other
countries, Home Minister Rafiqul Islam said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also exchanged notes on the avoidance of double
taxation and the prevention of fiscal evasion regarding taxes on
income between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
