<HEADLINE> No Security Threat to Warrant India's Nuclear Tests: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- There was "nothing extraordinary"
in the security environment in South Asia to warrant India's
nuclear tests in May, said Russian Ambassador to India Albert S.
Chernyshev.
</P>
<P>
"all countries have security concerns but we should take into
consideration whether these concerns are to be defended by a
nuclear weapon or not," said Chernyshev said in an exclusive
interview with the Pioneer daily Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We can imagine that the moon will fall on the earth tomorrow.
But that is not the reality. The concerns should be balanced and
correspond to reality," added Chernyshev.
</P>
<P>
While Indian politicians were talking about a China threat,
"the situation was never like China preparing to attack India,"
the Russian diplomat pointed out in the interview published here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He described the so-called China's assistance to Pakistan in
the areas of nuclear and missile technology as rumors, saying that
there were similar "rumors" about Western powers helping India to
develop its nuclear technology.
</P>
<P>
Chernyshev called on India to immediately begin negotiations on
the question of entering the non-proliferation regimes and sign
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
"You can criticize the NPT and the CTBT, but it is the maximum
as 150 countries have agreed to it," Chernyshev said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has consistently avoided a harsh criticism of India's
nuclear tests and defense cooperation between the two traditional
allies seemed to have been enhanced amid condemnations and
sanctions by the international community against India for the
nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have finalized a new 10-year defense
cooperation pact which will add punch to India's air and sea
defenses and give India its first anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Ambassador confirmed that Russian President Boris
Yeltsin is scheduled to visit New Delhi in December this year,
during which the two countries are expected to sign a declaration
of strategic partnership.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
