<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's 2nd Cellular Phone Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's second cellular
telephone network, Telecel Zimbabwe, went into operation
Wednesday, benefiting people of the capital Harare, the media
here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Telecel Zimbabwe declared it would invest about 60 million
U.S. Dollars over the next 10 years in a bid to make
communication in the country cheaper and more affordable.
</P>
<P>
Telecel Zimbabwe, as an indigenous community-driven company,
intends to take advantage of the technological revolution to bring
telecommunication services to some of the remote areas, thereby
enhancing both economic and social development of communities.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the company has set up five base stations and
subscribers can enjoy coverage in the Harare city center and its
peripherals, with eight more under construction and expected to
go live before late July to ensure a complete coverage of harare.
</P>
<P>
Launching the network's operations, Minister of Information,
Posts and Telecommunications Chen Chimutengwende said it was
pleasant to note that indigenous people were beginning to take an
active part in communications, a field in which the state-run
Post and Telecommunication Company has had a monopoly for a long
time. 
</P>
