<HEADLINE> China to Enforce Anti-Dumping Measures on Newsprint From Canada, ROK, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) announced here today that China will
take temporary anti-dumping measures against newsprint originated
from Canada, the Republic of Korea and the United States beginning
on July 10.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC officially began investigating cases involving the
alleged dumping of newsprint from these countries on December 10,
1997, in accordance with China's anti-dumping and anti-subsidy
regulations.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC and the General Administration of Customs has been
investigating dumping and the extent of dumping activities since
then, while the State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC), in
conjunction with related ministries, has been investigating the
extent of damages incurred.
</P>
<P>
The investigation showed that there was dumping of 17.11 to
78.93 percent of all newsprint imported from these countries, a
practice which has caused substantial damage to China's newsprint
industry.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC spokesman said today that according to investigation
results and the anti-dumping and anti-subsidy regulations, MOFTEC
decided to take the anti-dumping measures and that importers
should pay cash deposit in accordance with anti-dumping rulings.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that within 37 days of MOFTEC's
announcement, concerned parties could forward written comments and
demands to MOFTEC and SETC for the consideration of investigating
departments according to the law.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC and SETC will then continue to investigate and render a
final arbitration ruling in due time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
