<HEADLINE> Egypt, France to Follow up Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian and French foreign ministers
will meet later this month and exchange views on how to revive the
stalled Mideast peace process, the French ambassador said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Amr Moussa and Hubert Vedrine will meet in Paris on July 17 to
evaluation of Egyptian-French efforts in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss the initiative for an international
conference on Mideast peace jointly proposed in May by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and his French counterpart Jacques Chirac
in May, French Ambassador Jean Marc de la Sabliere to Cairo told
Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will brief Vedrine on the latest developments of the
U.S. stance after he finishes his consultations in Washington
within the coming days, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and France will be able to define their coming steps and
coordinate a joint drive in the coming stage in the light of the
U.S. stance and the developments of the situation in general, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa left here Thursday for Washington to initiate strategic
talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. They are
expected to discuss the American initiative to break the 15-month
deadlock in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has proposed a 13.1 percent Israeli troops withdrawal
from the West Bank. It is rejected by Israel but accepted by the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Sabliere underlined that the Egyptian-French efforts "back and
complement" the American role in the peace process and do not
substitute for it.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
1997 over Israeli construction of a new settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem and its reluctance to withdraw troops from the West
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
