<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Slips in Customer-Satisfaction Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- IBM fell from the top position
in a market-research firm's customer-satisfaction survey on
notebooks.
</P>
<P>
In Technology Business Research's second quarter survey,
conducted between May and June, IBM, previously a perennial winner
of the quarterly survey, lost out to Texas-based Dell Computer.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the past six quarters IBM has not
finished first in the survey. A total of 243 large corporations
were polled.
</P>
<P>
While Dell posted a customer-satisfaction score of 10.15 out of
12, IBM scored 9.95 compared to 10.31 in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The biggest complaint about the Big Blue was its slow repair
response time, said the survey. Customers expressed frustration
that IBM employees could not fix its product ThinkPads on site and
had to take them to an IBM repair center or to a reseller.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed customer problems with IBM's
pricing. But IBM said that the company's prices and warranty
service were on par with the rest of the notebook industry.
</P>
<P>
In the past six months, IBM started offering an upgrade to
on-site service in major metropolitan areas for 49 U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
