<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emergency Aid Workers Need Proper Training: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Emergency aid workers often receive
little training and warning about the living and working
conditions awaiting them in the field, and the recruitment
procedures used by many relief agencies are often less than
professional, said the World Health Organization (WHO) here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Many staff are recruited hurriedly and casually with little
time for references or checking of references," the WHO said in a
press release based on the findings of a study on the relief work
in Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda early this year.
</P>
<P>
"Briefing on security issues and political matters appears to
be especially deficient and staff sometimes feel they are placed
at unnecessary risk as a result," the study said.
</P>
<P>
Of the more than 200 relief workers questioned, 53 percent had
not received any personal medical briefing prior to departure and
20 percent of those surveyed had not had, or were not aware of,
whether their vaccination status had been verified.
</P>
<P>
Psychosocial health is also a concern to come out of the
study. Only half of the sample felt that they were able to
function well on the day they were interviewed and a high
proportion of respondents reported general fatigue (59 percent)
and headaches (50 percent).
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that much can be improved and hope the
experience of well-established agencies can be brought to bear,"
said Dr Harald Siem, chief of WHO's Inter-Agency Cooperation Unit
for Emergency and Humanitarian Action.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that our work will be a spur to the international
community as a whole," Siem said. "There is evidently a need to
protect humanitarian aid workers more effectively." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
