<HEADLINE> afgamAJD*B-jj~U.S. to Lift Sanction on Nigeria Only After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States government may not
lift existing sanctions on Nigeria as early as expected unless
democracy is restored in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is pegging the lifting on the release of all
political detainees and the rapid and transparent conclusion of
the transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
This is the key information a high-powered U.S. delegation
tried to let Nigerians know Wednesday at the end of its three-day
visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the delegation, U.S. Under-Secretary of State
for Political Affairs, Thomas Pickering, said in the Nigerian
capital Abuja that the early and unconditional release of
political detainees and prisoners, coupled with an evidence of
genuine democratization process, will open the doors for the
lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation arrived in Nigeria Monday night for talks
with the new leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar on the current
political crisis in Nigeria and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Pickering emphasized that although the Abubakar government
expressed interest on the lifting of sanctions, the U.S. insisted
on "an early and unconditional release of political prisoners and
a rapid movement towards a smooth, open, free and fair transition
to a civilian democratic government."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imposed limited sanctions on Nigeria in 1993 after
the then military government annulled the June 13 presidential
elections, which businessman-politician, late Moshood Abiola, was
believed to have won.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, including suspension of U.S. aid and visa ban
on senior officers of the military regime, became a comprehensive
ban on cooperation in the military field in 1995 when nine
minority activists were executed by the Nigerian government.
</P>
<P>
Abiola died of apparent heart attack after taken ill at a
meeting with government officials and Pickering's delegation
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was said to be one of a series for making
arrangements for the release of Abiola, who was detained four
years ago for declaring himself president of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The sudden death of Abiola has triggered off violent
demonstrations in southwestern Nigeria, where about 30 people
were feared dead.
</P>
<P>
A full postmortem is expected later Thursday to find the exact
cause of Abiola's death, at the request of his relatives and with
the help of a group of foreign pathologists.
</P>
<P>
The report of the autopsy will be very important to the
stability at the critical moment of Nigeria's political process,
which is to end with the military returning to where they came to
power years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
