<HEADLINE> Foreign Doctors Expected in Lagos for Abiola's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A team of foreign pathologists are
expected to arrive here Thursday to help find the real cause of
the death of Nigeria's number one political detainee Moshood
Abiola.
</P>
<P>
The pathologists are from Britain, the United States and
Canada at the invitation of the Nigerian government to involve in
the examination of the corpse of Abiola, who died apparently of
heart attack Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The government made the invitation at the request of some of
Abiola's relatives who disbelieved the reported cause of his
death.
</P>
<P>
The autopsy, originally planned to be conducted in the capital
Abuja, is expected to be carried out in Lagos where Abiola's
personal physician Dr. Ore Falomo insisted there are better
medical facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government Tuesday announced the sudden death of
Abiola after he was taken ill during a meeting "which was being
held by Nigerian and United States officials with him".
</P>
<P>
According to Thomas Pickering, the head of a high-powered U.S.
government delegation to Nigeria, the seemingly "clear and lucid"
Abiola had trouble in breathing in the middle of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Cough medicine and pain killer, as well as other temporary
measures, did not help improve his situation. Abiola was then
hurried to the presidential clinic where one and a half hours'
emergency treatment failed to save his life, Pickering told
reporters Wednesday at the end of his visit.
</P>
<P>
The death of Abiola on the brink of his release from four
years in detention has given rise to uncertainty to the political
crisis of the country.
</P>
<P>
Violation broke out Tuesday night after the news of his death
was spread to the south, the stronghold of supporters and
sympathizers of the presumed winner of the June 12, 1993
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 persons were feared dead during demonstrations to
protest Abiola's death.
</P>
<P>
To secure exactly what killed Abiola then has become a very
important thing that will have a big impact on the stability of
the west African country.
</P>
<P>
According to Falomo, arrangements had been concluded to give
the foreign medical experts "free hand to operate".
</P>
<P>
But he said he would not participate in the exercise because
he was not allowed access to Abiola in his life time, the Daily
Times quoted the physician as saying Wednesday, without giving
further details.
</P>
<P>
Falomo also declined to disclose the venue of the autopsy,
saying "it is only the people concerned with it that would know."
</P>
</TEXT>
