<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Currency Sees 2nd Day of Calm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's strained
financial markets enjoyed a second day of calm Wednesday, as an
eight-week speculative assault remained on hold.
</P>
<P>
With the relative calm in the currency market spilling over to
the bond and equities markets, analysts are hoping the worst is
over and that the Rand is in consolidation mode, South Africa
newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said currency stability was the key to attracting new
foreign investment in South Africa's bond market, which was
looking cheap. However, Wednesday's stillness could just be the
silence before the next storm.
</P>
<P>
The Rand closed in Johannesburg on Wednesday at 6.14 Rand to
the Dollar, well up from its recent low of 6.75, but still over
20 percent beneath its value against the Dollar in late May.
</P>
<P>
The Rand held its own despite rumors that Reserve Bank deputy
governor James Cross was set to resign over the appointment of
Labor Minister Tito Mboweni to lead the bank next year.
</P>
<P>
Cross flatly denied the rumors, saying he would see out his
full term which ends in December, 2001, and that Mboweni had his
full support.
</P>
<P>
The Rand and bonds were also helped by the assurance of
Mboweni that he would not interfere with the bank's independence,
nor hesitate to dish out stiff monetary medicine if the economy
sickened.
</P>
<P>
The Rand, which has been hammered by foreign speculators since
late May, hit an all-time low of 6.75 Rand against the Dollar on
Monday, as investors reacted with shock to the news that Mboweni
would replace governor Chris Stals after the latter's retirement
in August 1999.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni on Wednesday dismissed fears that the African National
Congress (ANC) would change the constitution ensuring the central
bank's independence if it won a two-thirds majority in next
year's general election, a requirement for alteration of the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
He also said he was prepared to make harsh choices in the face
of possible financial turmoil, such as raising interest rates.
The Reserve Bank's recent interest rate hikes have drawn scathing
criticism from labor unions.
</P>
<P>
"I know that when interest rates bite at some point, some
people will complain... but if we have to dish out that kind of
medicine from time to time, we will have to do it," Mboweni said.
</P>
<P>
But analysts remained wary of forecasting an end to the
currency's misery and warned confidence had been badly shaken and
would not speedily return.
</P>
<P>
South African Finance Minister Trevor Manuel on Wednesday also
showed his support for Mboweni, saying that media criticism of
Mboweni's appointment stemmed from "the racism deep within" some
individuals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
