<HEADLINE> Rare Tree Zone Expanded in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province,
known as the "kingdom of plants," has expanded the growing area of
taiwania cryptomerioides hayata (a kind of China fir) to more than
13,300 ha, believed to be the largest such tract of its kind in
the world.
</P>
<P>
The area, in Baoshan Prefecture, has a timber reserve of
700,000 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Taiwania cryptomerioides hayata, a rare species native to
Yunnan and Guizhou Provinces, is under top state protection. The
tree is fast-growing and can grow to a height of eight meters.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture has allocated 10 million yuan for planting
saplings since the mid-1980s and has designated five standing
timber zones, the largest covering 4,300 ha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
