<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Pays Surprise Visit to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
arrived in northeastern Libya Thursday on a surprise visit to meet
with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi who is recovering from a
fractured hip bone, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
There was no announcement of the purpose of the visit.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi broke a hip bone after he fell during exercising on
Monday. Doctors said they had succeeded in fixing the fracture
with a platinum nail and that they were able to adjust the hip
bone to its normal position.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak Wednesday offered to send a medical team to help Libyan
doctors treat Gaddafi's fractured hip bone.
</P>
<P>
The news agency did not mention what kind of transportation
Mubarak used Thursday morning to reach Baida, about 770 kilometers
east of the capital Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
In previous trips to Libya in the past six years, the president
flew from Cairo to somewhere near the Egyptian-Libyan border and
then drove across it, bowing to a U.N. air embargo on Libya.
</P>
<P>
The air embargo was imposed in 1992 after Gaddafi refused to
hand over two Libyans suspected of bombing an American airliner
over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988. A total of 270 people were
killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Organization of African Unity urged member
states to ignore the air embargo starting October. The Arab League
said it is considering following suit.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi has scuttled his week-long visit to Egypt slated early
in June, without giving reasons. But Mubarak told reporters that
Gaddafi has a mild tonsil and was expected to make the trip in 10
to 15 days. The second date for the trip was also missed.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian and Libyan officials denied a report that Gaddafi had
postponed the visit because of a failed attempt to kill him.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi reportedly came under an attack in the Mediterranean
city of Benghazi in which he was slightly wounded and many of his
bodyguards were hurt. Libya said it was "sheer lies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
