<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Embattled Ugandan Mayor Faces Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- When Kampala Mayor Hajji Nasser
Sebaggala is still fighting for his freedom in the United States,
there is report here saying Interpol Uganda will question him on
his return, which adds more uncertainty to the future of the
embattled mayor.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Internal Affairs Tom Butime told parliament
Wednesday that the case is by no means over. Instead, it's just
beginning. The Interpol will quiz the mayor as soon as he returns
home.
</P>
<P>
The mayor's accomplices in Uganda who made the altered checks
are already questioned by the police, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala was arrested in New York on June 13 for making false
statements to U.S. customs officers when he was about to board a
Brussels-bound Sabena flight en route to Entebbe.
</P>
<P>
Reports said he did not declare that he was carrying 100,800
U.S. Dollars in cash, which is well over the allowed maximum
amount of 10,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a Boston grand jury placed in another six counts of
check frauds involving four transactions totalling 191,000
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
These charges against Sebaggala date back to February, 1997
when he allegedly deposited two altered checks for a total of
138,000 Dollars into his account in Bank Boston.
</P>
<P>
The mayor is thus charged with both Federal and State
offences. Making a false customs declaration is a federal offence
but depositing fraudulent checks is an offence under the
jurisdiction of the State of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, the mayor may be sentenced to a prison term of
no less than 30 years not including a colossal sum of fine.
</P>
<P>
After his arraignment in June, Sebaggala was released from
jail and put under the custody of Uganda's Ambassador to the
United Nations, Prof. Semakula Kiwanuka on condition that he
doesn't leave New York.
</P>
<P>
With the defense lawyers' paying 50,000 Dollar bond to a
federal court in Brooklyn, New York, the case of Sebaggala was
shifted from New York to Boston where the offences were allegedly
committed.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala's lawyer said earlier this month:"This is a special
kind of bond. It is not a bond in the sense of a bail bond. It is
simply to ensure his (Sebaggala's) presence in Boston."
</P>
<P>
Reports revealed that the mayor needs some 100,000 Dollars to
be bailed out and his staunch supporters back home tried to raise
money for his freedom and already sent it to the needy mayor.
</P>
<P>
His supporters are quite unsatisfied with the government's
stance on the matter.
</P>
<P>
They accused the government of being reluctant to help the
democratically elected mayor, saying that now President Yoweri
Museveni who they believe is closer to the U.S. should help the
mayor out.
</P>
<P>
The government should not step back from the case, leaving the
mayor to fend for himself, they argued.
</P>
<P>
The minister of internal affairs told the parliament on
Wednesday that the mayor in trouble is getting help from Uganda's
Ambassadors to the United Nations and the United States. He is
fed and housed in the ambassador's residence free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The authorities held that the mayor had committed all these
offences in his private capacity and the government is not in a
position to meddle in the matter.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the mayor got into trouble, his main opponents
demanded the city council to remove him from the top post of the
capital city, citing his bad reputation produced from the
offences and his poor qualifications required of the post.
</P>
<P>
They said the mayor, who was elected in April this year,
cannot speak good English and is short of an A level certificate
the mayorship demands.
</P>
<P>
As the mayor is still struggling for his freedom in the United
States, the Interpol back home has already designed the
questionnaire against him, making his position as Kampala mayor
extremely shaky.
</P>
<P>
Although he called to his supporters here the other day saying
he is okay and confident in winning his freedom at last, nobody
knows what is to await him when he steps back on Ugandan soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Dips on Weak Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The negative impact of a weak
Japanese yen drove the Australian dollar more than half a U.S.
cent lower Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney Thursday, the local currency was buying
61.53 U.S. cents from Wednesday's close of 62.09 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"It is reacting quite a lot to Asian weakness and weakness in
the Japanese yen," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar was trading at 140.16 Japanese yen, from 139.57
yen Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main focus for the Australian dollar continued to be Asia,
the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Overnight the Australian unit followed the yen down after
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto indicated that any tax
cuts would not be forthcoming this year.
</P>
<P>
The expected tax package had been seen as a major component of
Japan's recovery from recession.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the Australian dollar was trading at 86.18
Japanese yen from 86.15 yen and 1.1207 German marks from 1.1281
marks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
