<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Prices Close Lower in Tokyo on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed lower in Tokyo
Thursday on profit taking by institutions amid slow trading.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 84.02 points, or 0.51
percent, from Wednesday's close to finish at 16,446.95.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 6.12 points or 0.48 percent to
1,262.28.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the major section decreased to an estimated 400
million shares from 517.51 million shares traded Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Yuasa, a battery maker, was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
A wide variety of domestic demand-sensitive issues, including
steel, bank and construction stocks, fell after seeing big gains
last week when the Nikkei leapt more than 1,300 points on growing
expectations of future permanent tax cuts to boost the flagging
economy, traders said.
</P>
<P>
More selling of cross-held shares among Japanese corporations
also contributed to the decline, they said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's slide, however, was slowed somewhat by a heavy dose
of buying-backs among foreign brokerages who had been net sellers
of Japanese stocks from March through the end of May.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outpaced gainers 786 to 353, with 134 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
