<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Creating Comfortable Urban Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Public order is no longer the top
concern of residents in this capital city of south China's
Guangdong Province thanks to city government efforts to create
better living conditions along with economic development.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the city has injected 2.5 billion
yuan to improve the functioning of law enforcement departments. As
a result, the incidence of crime began to drop in 1995 and
urbanites are now enjoying greater security.
</P>
<P>
During this period, the city also spent 28.5 billion yuan
building its infrastructure, an average annual increase of 51
percent, considerably easing the problems of energy,
transportation and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou now has nearly two million telephone lines, as well
as 15 public buses per 10,000 people. And greenery now covers 25
percent of the city.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city has taken measures to treat industrial
pollution and has moved several polluting factories out of the
downtown area, and motor vehicles in Guangzhou have now begun to
use unleaded gasoline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Denies Making Request to Maintain Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has denied reports that it has
asked the United Nations Sanctions Committee to allow it to
maintain Iraqi planes, saying that Iraq itself made the request,
the Jordan Times daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq submitted this request to the U.N. Sanctions Committee,
and we believe that it was their right to have their planes
maintained," Jordanian Minister of Transport, Post and
Telecommunications Sami Gammo told the semi-official daily.
</P>
<P>
Gammo did not say when Iraq made the request and whether the
committee has agreed to it.
</P>
<P>
Press reports have said that Jordan made the request which was
rejected by the Sanctions Committee several days ago.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Jordan has the intention to maintain six
Iraqi commercial planes left in the kingdom after the 1990 Gulf
crisis caused by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The planes have been staying at the Queen Alia International
Airport, some 50 kilometers south of Amman.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed economic sanctions on Iraq in
1990, banning its business and commercial activities with other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
