<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Students Receive Training on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 80 Tanzanian students
have attended a training course to learn about Internet since
January this year.
</P>
<P>
The students have been able to gain knowledge concerning
computer, chemistry and engineering at the Computing Center of
the University of Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by The Guardian on Thursday, the course
is under a program of the African Virtual University (AVU), a
project of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The AVU mission is to take advantage of modern information
technology to make more people in sub-Saharan Africa to gain
access to education resources in the world.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is among six countries in sub-Saharan Africa being
covered by the program which has links with the University of New
Jersy, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Other countries are Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia, Zimbabwe and
Ghana. Some 12 centers in those countries offer a wide range of
studies to students on Internet.
</P>
<P>
Existing college programs in sub-Saharan Africa are inadequate
to meet students' rapidly increasing demands for knowledge, said
an official at the University of Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the university installed a high-power satellite
dish that will provide efficient communication link with the AVU
project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
