<HEADLINE> Blair Meets with Protestant Orangemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
was holding talks Thursday morning in Downing Street with four
senior Orangemen involved in the Portadown stand-off to discuss
the parade crisis.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said the prime minister did not
intend to drop a ban on Orangemen marching along the Garvaghy Road
in Portadown, 50 kilometers southwest of Provincial capital
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The meeting followed another night of violence and
demonstration in the province during which police warned people
not to travel unless the journey was essential.
</P>
<P>
The parade traditionally uses the route of Garvaghy Road area
but was banned this year by the independent Parades Commission,
and the security forces have mounted a massive operation to keep
protesters out, leading to a stand-off with the Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Northern Ireland's Democratic Unionist Party leader
Ian Paisley urged Blair to "see sense" and reverse the parade
ban. Paisley is a well-known figure in Northern Ireland who is
opposed to the peace agreement reached in April and endorsed in
May in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
The Protestant Orangemen also warned they could paralyse the
province "within hours" if the parade was not allowed to continue
through the Catholic area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
