<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Bank Chief Criticizes Price Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Issac Takawira, chief executive of
Barclays Bank of Zimbabwe has warned that government plans to
re-introduce price controls will create market distortions and
fuel shortages which can lead to smuggling and parallel markets.
</P>
<P>
He told a Zimbabwe Economic Society meeting that price
controls prolonged monopolies through discouraging new entrants
to the industry because of perceived limited profit
opportunities, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The answer does not lie in controlling the end price alone
without controlling prices of inputs in the production process,"
but "lies in prudent management of the economy, downsizing the
public sector to a level sustainable by reasonable rates of taxes
and borrowings," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a move described by analysts as a negation of donor-backed
economic reforms, the government gazetted last month the price of
mealie-meal and other basic food commodities saying it was
protecting citizens from unjustified hikes by manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that the government is undoing some of the
major achievements made in the past few years," Takawira said.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's problems emanated from the high public
debt which needed to be reduced to a sustainable level.
</P>
<P>
This could be achieved through accelerating the privatization
of parastatals proceeds of which would be used :5 reduce the
fiscal deficit, inflation and interest rates, according to
Takawira.
</P>
<P>
The resulting stable macro economic environment will encourage
savings and new investment which will generate growth and
employment, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We all need to understand that there are no quick fixes,
there is no substitute for sound economic management," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
