<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Deals 30 Billion U.S. Dollars in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign exchange
transactions exceeded 31.2 billion U.S. dollars on 124 trading
days in the first half of this year, according to statistics just
released by the China Foreign Exchange Trading System.
</P>
<P>
Daily transactions averaged 252 million U.S. dollars,
figures show.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, U.S.-dollar trading accounted for 94 percent or
29.2 billion dollars. Hong Kong dollars and Japan yen made up 5
percent and one percent, respectively, or 13.1 billion HK dollars
and 43.3 billion yen.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of the year, the U.S. dollar was
basically stable, valued at between 8.28 and 8.27 against the RMB
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The HK dollar showed a slight downturn against the RMB yuan
during the period at 1.0683 on June 30, dropping 16 points from
the figure at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Japanese currency against the RMB yuan tended up marginally at
the start of the year, and dropped all the way down to 5.8737 on
June 30, slumping 4,788 points from the last trading day of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
