<HEADLINE> Over 50 Families Invade Commercial Farms in N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 families have invaded
a farm in Karoi, north Zimbabwe and 20 former freedom fighters
allocated themselves land on a state farm.
</P>
<P>
The number has been increasing since Monday when the first
batch of the Karoi families began erecting shelters at Laughing
Hills farm in Karoi, the Daily Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They claim they are irked by delays in the government's
resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
More families were expected to join them, Hanlory and Highdale
farms were said to be the next targets, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, the people moved in at about midday
on Monday. There were no immediate signs that the people would
leave the farms. A political solution to the problem was being
sought.
</P>
<P>
Villagers held a meeting Tuesday with officials from the
Ministry of Local Government and National Housing, but remained
adamant that they would not leave. They demanded to have July 27
as the deadline for resettlement and that none of them be evicted
without being resettled.
</P>
<P>
Although all land seizures by land-hungry communities are
illegal, no arrest has been made. Police said they were
monitoring the situation, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, about a thousand farmers in east Zimbabwe invade
four white peopel's farms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
