<HEADLINE> Fewer Overseas Buyers at Art Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Fewer overseas buyers than
expected turned up at an art auction that closed here Tuesday,
cooling the atmosphere of the event.
</P>
<P>
The Duoyunxuan Arts Auction Company, which was a pioneer art
auction company five years ago, attracted some 40 overseas buyers
and more than 100 domestic buyers to its latest sale.
</P>
<P>
Previously, according to general manager Zhu Junbo, the ratio
of overseas buyers over domestic ones was ten to seven. Zhu
attributed the decrease of overseas buyers to the economic
crisis in southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The two-day auction sold 62 per cent of the works offered for
sale, including Chinese and Western paintings, calligraphy,
sculpture, curios, and rare books, for a total of 23.21 million
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
