<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Golkar Opens Extraordinary Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
opened here Thursday the ruling Golkar's extraordinary congress,
calling on the people to sustain the momentum of the reform
movement.
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts have brought us advantages. Let us not render them
useless," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie told the congress that Indonesia needs to earn more
foreign exchange to restart the economy, considering that not all
aspects of the economy have been paralyzed by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I understand that many people are still not satisfied with all
the improvements we have made. But I believe we are making
significant improvements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic crisis, he said, Golkar has to brace
itself for the future through self-introspection and a better
vision of the future.
</P>
<P>
On the election of Golkar's new chairman, the president said
Golkar leaders should be chosen by "those at the bottom" of the
party and not by "those at the top."
</P>
<P>
Its future leaders should be able to make their own decisions
without seeking the approval of other groups in efforts to
revitalize the party, Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
Several candidates have been proposed by various sections of
the organization to replace the current chairman, Harmoko.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that former Defense Minister Edi Sudradjat and
Minister/Secretary of State Akbar Tanjung are the strongest
candidates. While retired Armed Forces officials are behind Edi's
nomination, Akbar is reportedly supported by the Armed Forces
Headquarters. For most of the country's nearly 53 years of
independence, the military has played an important role in
political life.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, the congress will discuss new
Golkar statutes including the abolition of the board of patrons,
board of advisors and board of councilors.
</P>
<P>
Based on current Golkar rules and regulations, the board of
patrons headed by former President Soeharto has extensive
authority and the right to annul policies adopted by the head of
the Golkar executive board.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the general elections in May or June next year,
Habibie said Golkar will compete not only against the United
Development Party and the Indonesian Democratic Party but also
against new parties that have recently been set up.
</P>
<P>
Under Soeharto's rule, only Golkar and two minority parties
were allowed to contest elections. Golkar, established in 1964 as
an amalgamation of seven organizations which include the armed
forces, labor organizations and cooperative movements, has won all
the seven general elections in the past.
</P>
<P>
The three-day congress i not attended by the chairman of its
Board of Patrons, Soeharto. The former president resigned on May
21 amid strong public pressure calling for political reforms.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the extraordinary congress organizing committee
Waskito Reksosoedirdjo said Soeharto had been invited to the
congress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
