<HEADLINE> NATO Threatens Actions on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) will act over the Kosovo issue unless Belgrade
accepts the Contact Group's ceasefire demand, German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made the remarks after arriving at the Rinas airport in
Tirana.
</P>
<P>
He said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would and should
accept the Contact Group's ceasefire demand, made at the Bonn
conference Wednesday, as a first step toward the settlement of the
Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
If Belgrade turns a deaf ear to the demand, then NATO will take
actions, the visiting foreign minister added.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, Kinkel briefed Albanian President Rexhap
Mejdani on the Contact Group's Bonn meeting.
</P>
<P>
In response, Mejdani was regretful for the long-delayed
settlement of the Kosovo issue, and in a statement, issued by his
press and information office, expressed doubts on the possibility
of resolving the Kosovo issue through political and diplomatic
means.
</P>
<P>
He urged the international community to send more forces to
Kosovo in a bid to increase the international diplomatic efforts
in the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group grouping Britain, France, Germany, Italy,
Russia and the United States has called for an immediate cessation
of hostilities in Kosovo to pave way for continuous talks between
Belgrade and the Kosovo Albanian leadership on additional
confidence-building measures and the future status of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel began his trip to Albania and Macedonia on Wednesday to
discuss the Kosovo crisis, and is scheduled to inspect the
refugees Thursday in the border area between Albania and
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
