<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans' Leisure Activities Surveyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- More Americans would rather
read a book, watch television, plant trees or flowers than spend
time with their families, a survey said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey of 1,007 adults, conducted by the Harris
Poll of Americans' leisure activities, showed that 30 percent of
them chose reading, 21 percent chose watching television, 14
percent chose gardening as their favorite pastimes, only 13
percent chose spending time with families.
</P>
<P>
Other favorites include fishing (11 percent), team sports (9
percent) and sewing (8 percent).
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that the Americans have about 20 hours a
week for leisure, little changed in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
