<HEADLINE> Relics Unearthered in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists working in the
eastern part of Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region recently
unearthed extensive Xinglongwa Culture ruins dating back some
8,000 years.
</P>
<P>
The archaeological team unearthed numerous pieces of pottery,
stone objects and more than 200 foundations of houses
characteristic of the primitive society from an over 60,000
sq.m. site.
</P>
<P>
Beichengzi, the Chinese name for the site, is twice as large
as the Xinglongwa ruins which were discovered nearby in the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say the ruins will provide valuable
clues for further research of ancient civilizations and social
development in Inner Mongolia and northeast China's Liaoning
Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
