<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Will Need Master Academicians in 21st Century  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China will need a great number of
men of letter, scholars and master academicians to restore its
cultural glory, sources from the prestigious Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences (CASS) said here today.
</P>
<P>
At the academy's graduation ceremony for graduate students,
Prof. Fang Keli urged that first-rate scholars must be nurtured
and cultivated in this era when knowledge is vital for China's
development.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Fang, president of the academy's graduate college, said
this must be done quickly as it will affect the image of China, a
country which has a 2,000-year-old tradition of academia and has
produced tens of thousands of outstanding scholars who have
contributed to world civilization.
</P>
<P>
However, this tradition was suspended during the chaotic
Cultural Revolution (1966-76) when intellectuals, who were defined
as bad elements compared to workers and farmers, were persecuted
and even killed.
</P>
<P>
The CASS has been home to many of the country's most
influential scholars, including Guo Moruo, the famous writer and
historian, and Hu Qiaomu, former secretary to the late Chairman
Mao Zedong, and many other eminent philosophers, archeologists and
economists.
</P>
<P>
But most of these authoritative geniuses have passed away or
are now living their final days, and 80 percent of the academy's
leading scholars will retire by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Fang went on to say that the academy has been carring out
a program to cultivate future scholars, and 200 bright youngsters
have been selected to inherit this academic legacy.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Academy is also working to attract established
scholars from outside its walls, vowing to provide better housing,
higher salaries and more opportunities to visit abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
