<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
Thursday closed marginally up but off its highs as the weaker
currency market dampened sentiment, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed up 14.8 points, or 0.53
percent, at 2788.9, off a high of 2799.9 and a low of 2774.1.
</P>
<P>
The market opened stronger on a positive lead from Wall Street
overnight, where the Dow Jones Industrial Average climbed 89.93
points to 9174.97.
</P>
<P>
But weakness on Japanese and Hong Kong markets coupled with the
fall in the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar kept the local
bourse from gaining more ground, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index closed up 25.4 points at 4898.6 and
the All Resources Index gained 6.3 points to 1086.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 289.68 million valued at 651.9 million
U.S. dollars, with rises outnumbering falls by 576 to 484.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed local trade at 61.5 U.S. cents
after closing at 62.09 U.S. cents Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia shares continued to surge
Thursday, peaking at a new intra-day record high of 20.33
Australian dollars after strong institutional buying and settling
at a record close of 20.13 Australian dollars, up 16 cents.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank gained 24 cents to 22.6 Australian
dollars, Westpac Banking Corp. gained 10 cents to 10.67 Australian
dollars and ANZ Banking Group dipped 7 cents to 11.73 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, BHP climbed 16 cents to 14.36
Australian dollars and Rio Tinto rose 15 cents to 19.20 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
A fall in New York gold bullion prices overnight after the
European Central Bank said it would hold only 15 percent of its
exchange reserves in gold pushed the gold index down 6.3 points,
or 0.56 percent, to 1118.2.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trade in gold bullion closed 2.8 U.S. dollars lower at
292.75 U.S. dollars an ounce, following the European announcement
on gold reserves. 
</P>
