<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Doctors in Lagos for Abiola's Autopsy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A team of foreign pathologists have
arrived here to help find the real cause of the death of
Nigeria's number one political detainee Moshood Abiola.
</P>
<P>
The pathologists come from Britain, the United States and
Canada at the invitation of the Nigerian government to involve in
the examination of the corpse of Abiola, who died apparently of
heart attack Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The government made the invitation at the request of some of
Abiola's relatives who disbelieved the reported cause of his
death.
</P>
<P>
The autopsy, originally planned to be conducted in the capital
Abuja, is expected to be carried out Thursday here in Lagos where
Abiola's personal physician Dr. Ore Falomo insisted there are
better medical facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government Tuesday announced the sudden death of
Abiola after he was taken ill during a meeting "which was being
held by Nigerian and United States officials with him".
</P>
<P>
According to Thomas Pickering, the head of a high-powered U.S.
government delegation to Nigeria, the seemingly "clear and lucid"
Abiola had trouble in breathing in the middle of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Cough medicine and pain killer, as well as other temporary
measures, did not help improve his situation. Abiola was then
hurried to the presidential clinic where one and a half hours'
emergency treatment failed to save his life, Pickering told
reporters Wednesday at the end of his visit.
</P>
<P>
The death of Abiola on the brink of his release from four
years in detention has given rise to uncertainty to the political
crisis of the country.
</P>
<P>
Violation broke out Tuesday night after the news of his death
was spread to the south, the stronghold of supporters and
sympathizers of the presumed June 12, 1993 presidential election
winner.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 persons were feared dead during demonstrations to
protest Abiola's death.
</P>
<P>
To secure exactly what killed Abiola then has become a very
important thing that will have a big impact on the stability of
the west African country.
</P>
<P>
According to Falomo, arrangements had been concluded to give
the foreign medical experts "free hand to operate" and an autopsy
report may be out later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But he said he would not participate in the exercise because
he was not allowed access to Abiola in his life time, the Daily
Times quoted the physician as saying, without giving further
details.
</P>
<P>
Falomo also declined to disclose the venue of the autopsy,
saying "it is only the people concerned with it that would know."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Rates S. Africa as Attractive Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States State
Department has rated South Africa as an "attractive" destination
for U.S. business, with "significant growth potential."
</P>
<P>
However, delays in privatization in South Africa may slow the
pace of capital inflows this year, the department said in its
latest annual survey of South Africa's investment climate,
Business Day paper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among the few new problem areas cited is South Africa's draft
competition bill, which is seen as giving the trade and industry
minister too much discretion to block business mergers and
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
Also of concern are "reported" plans to bar companies in South
Africa from complying with "extraterritorial" laws such the U.S.
Helms-Burton act, which seeks to penalize firms that invest in
Cuba, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
It notes that U.S. firms "do experience some problems" in
South Africa with intellectual property protection, even though
South African laws and practices are "generally in conformity"
with those of industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
However, efforts to crack down on software piracy "have borne
fruit." Just less than half the software installed in South
Africa is now said to be illegally copied, which is comparable to
European levels.
</P>
<P>
Although South Africa's highly developed capital markets are
seen as a plus for direct investors, the report warns that
insider trading is "poorly" regulated and seldom investigated.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's labor costs are low relative to Western
industrialized countries but productivity is also lower, the
report notes.
</P>
<P>
The labor-management relationship is described as being amid a
"challenging" process of change. "Reaching common ground on a set
of policies to foster job creation remains one of the most
pressing challenges," it says.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has investment agreements with Canada and most
European countries, but not the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Formal negotiations have proved unproductive," although a
bilateral tax treaty is now in effect, the survey says.
</P>
<P>
While crime is a serious problem, the statistics may be
"misleading" because incidents are being reported and recorded
more efficiently than in the apartheid era, it says.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the largest single source of foreign
direct investment last year.
</P>
<P>
However, flows "are expected to taper off in 1998, given
delays in privatization efforts".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
