<HEADLINE> Philippine Army, MILF Rebels Clash Anew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Government troops, backed by heavy
artillery and attack helicopters, Thursday continued pounding on
two village strongholds held by some 200 Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) rebels in Pigcawayan, Cotabato, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
As of 2 p.m. Thursday, government forces persisted in
delivering heavy blows to the rebels, who were reportedly
resisting with heavy machine-gun fire, mortar shelling and rocket
propelled grenades, the Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Pigcawayan Mayor Jun Garcesa as saying the
intense fighting, which started around 5:00 a.m. Thursday, was
still going on at two remote villages.
</P>
<P>
Casualties from both sides are yet to be determined, Garcesa
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the fighting occurred following a series of
reported harassment and cattle-rustling activities in the vicinity
by MILF men during the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the clashes, some 1,000 local residents from
four villages have been reportedly evacuated to safer grounds to
avoid being caught in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
Major Rosque Garingalao, spokesman of the army's Sixth Infantry
Division, denied that the army started the fight with the MILF,
saying they just retaliated after the rebels ambushed patrol
elements of the military. 
</P>
