<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 75 Lebanese Charged for Spying for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese military prosecutor Nasri
Lahoud has charged 75 members of an underground ring for handing
over information on Lebanese and Syrian troops movement and the
activities of anti-occupation guerrillas to Israeli intelligence.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper the Daily Star Thursday quoted Lahoud's
indictment as saying that the suspects, only 17 members of whom
have been taken into custody so far, are also accused of "entering
enemy territory."
</P>
<P>
The group was formed in 1995 to monitor military movements in
areas outside the Israeli-occupied zone and Syrian military bases
near Mazzeh, east of Syrian capital Damascus, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas cross-border attack.
</P>
<P>
The suspects were said to have sent letters written in
invisible ink to contacts in Athens. One of them allegedly
received 7,300 U.S. dollars for the 11 letters sent to the Greek
capital.
</P>
<P>
The ring was dismantled after Raja Ward, deputy head of the
South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia's intelligence services in the
eastern sector of the occupied zone, surrendered to the Lebanese
army a fortnight ago, the paper quoted a judicial source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-member SLA has been helping Israeli forces to patrol
its occupied south Lebanon and policing Lebanon's central
Christian town of Jezzine, just north to the zone.
</P>
<P>
Ward, a 37-year-old Lebanese Druze, gave information to the
authorities about a network of 22 Lebanese Druze and Shiite
Muslims who fed information to the Israeli army on the activities
of Hezbollah fighters, the Lebanese army and the Syrian army, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, backed by Iran, is leading a
guerrilla war to oust Israeli occupying forces from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria has deployed a 40,000-strong troops in Lebanon to help
maintain the security of the country which is recovering from the
1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the indictments are required to undergo a
review by a military investigating magistrate after further
investigations into the matter before a trial can begin at the
military tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
