<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on U.S.-Taiwan Relations after Clinton's China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The key to ensuring the healthy and
stable growth of Sino-U.S. relations lies in properly handling the
Taiwan issue, the most important and sensative part of the
bilateral ties, Foreign Ministry spokesman Tang Guoqiang stated
today.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the statement in response to a question on
U.S.-Taiwan relations after U.S. President Bill Clinton's state
visit to China, which ended on July 3.
</P>
<P>
"There is only one China and Taiwan is part of China. The
government of the People's Republic of China is the sole legitimate
government representing the whole of China," Tang said, adding
that this is a fact accepted universally by the United Nations and
the international community.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The leaders of the United States have time and again
explicitly made the commitment to pursue the 'One China' policy
and abide by the principles set forth in the three Sino-U.S. joint
communiques on different occasions. The United States has
committed itself not to support the independence of Taiwan; not to
support the concept of 'One China, One Taiwan' or 'Two Chinas';
and not to support Taiwan's entry into the United Nations and all
other international organizations composed of sovereign states."
</P>
<P>
Tang indicated that President Clinton reiterated the above
commitments of the United States in his recent China visit.
</P>
<P>
"We attach great importance to these commitments made by
the U.S. side," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"History of the development of Sino-U.S. relations has shown
that whenever the Taiwan issue is handled correctly,
Sino-U.S. ties will grow smoothly. Otherwise, Sino-U.S. relations
will suffer from setbacks, and even retrogression," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tang indicated that China resolutely opposes the Taiwan
Relations Act, which runs counter to the commitments made by the
U.S. government in the three joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the improvement and development of
Sino-U.S. relationship are not only in the common interests of the
two countries, but also conducive to world peace, stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
The mutual visits paid by the two heads of state will advance
bilateral ties into a new stage and the improvement of bilateral
relations will surely have a positive impact on improving
relations across the Taiwan Straits, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the Taiwan authorities will have a clear
understanding of the current situation, face realities, bear the
just national cause in mind, return to the 'One China' stand as
soon as possible and respond promptly to our call on holding
political negotiations. They should no longer do what damages
national interests and dignity," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
