<HEADLINE> Chinese Cities Set to Restrict Cigarette Sales to Teens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The State Tobacco Monopoly Bureau
has instructed department stores in 18 Chinese cities to
prominently display signs warning teenagers of the dangers of
smoking.
</P>
<P>
The signs will be in place by July 10 and will read: "State
Tobacco Monopoly Bureau Warning: Sales of Cigarettes to Primary
and Middle School Students Are Prohibited".
</P>
<P>
The warnings will be introduced to 18 cities -- Beijing,
Tianjin, Dalian, Shenyang, Shanghai, Nanjing, Wuhan, Fuzhou,
Xiamen, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Dongguan, Shantou, Haikou,
Chengdu, Chongqing and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The bureau will launch a series of activities to convince
primary and middle school students to avoid the use of tobacco.
</P>
