<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Accepts in Principle Israeli Request for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has accepted "in principle" an
Israeli request for maintenance of its civilian planes by the
Jordanian Civil Aviation Authority (CAA), the Jordan Times daily
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"In principle, we accepted the request but we informed them
that technical details should be discussed before reaching an
agreement," CAA head Jasser Ziyad told the semi-official daily.
</P>
<P>
Meetings are expected to be held in weeks by a technical
committee of the two countries in a bid to reach a memorandum of
understanding on the issue, Ziyad said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Israel put forward the request for Jordan's
help to maintain its commercial planes during a recent bilateral
meeting held under the framework of a peace treaty signed by the
two countries in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Apparently, the Israelis believe that maintaining their planes
in Jordan will cost them less than any other places," Ziyad said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has contracts with Turkey and Chile to repair its
commercial planes and jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel began to carry out civil aviation cooperation
after signing the peace treaty. Commercial flights started to
shuttle between Amman and Tel Aviv in 1996. The two sides have
also agreed to jointly use the airport in Jordan's Red Sea port
city of Aqaba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
