<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 08:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestine Wishes for Full U.N. Membership by 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Envoy to the United
Nations Nasser al-Kodwa Thursday expressed the hope that the world
organization would accept Palestine as a member state by next year.
</P>
<P>
Kodwa made the remarks to the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio
two days after the U.N. General Assembly adopted the
Arab-sponsored resolution to upgrade Palestine's status from
observer to nonvoting member, which is near statehood.
</P>
<P>
The voting was 124 for, four against, with 10 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution reflects the international community's
acceptance of Palestine as a political entity and as a future
independent state, said Kodwa.
</P>
<P>
"It mirrors a strong global support for the Palestinians,"
Kodwa told the radio over telephone from New York.
</P>
<P>
The decision grants rights and additional privileges to
Palestinians so that they can participate in General Assembly
debates and submit draft proposals on Palestine, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he expects his country would be granted a full member
status in the near future, maybe by next year.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the General Assembly would accept Palestine as a
U.N. member state at its upcoming 53rd session," which runs from
September 1998 to September 1999.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's resolution was voted against by Israel, the United
States and two Pacific island countries, the Marshall Islands and
Micronesia.
</P>
<P>
With new powers at hand, Palestinian representatives can raise
issues of the peace process in the assembly and co-sponsor draft
resolutions on Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
But the representatives can not vote or put forward candidates
for U.N. committees, such as the Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
