<HEADLINE> Housing Management Requires Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The China Consumers Association
reports that the quality of housing has emerged as a major
complaint from Chinese consumers.
</P>
<P>
Association statistics show that the number of housing
complaints filed in the second quarter of this year jumped by 77.4
percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Complaints mainly focus on poor quality, false advertising,
misappropriation of housing space, breaches of contracts,
substandard contracts and housing management problems.
</P>
<P>
An association spokesman pointed out that the rising number of
complaints reveals the urgent need to improve the management of
China's fledging housing market.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the concern will continue to rise as more Chinese
citizens purchase homes as part of market reform which is
replacing the traditional welfare allocation system for public
housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
