<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Expand Desalinization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China currently desalts over
four million tons of water each year to supply booming coastal
cities.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, the largest port city in north China, leads the nation
in daily desalinization output of 6,000 tons, or approximately half
of the country's annual output.
</P>
<P>
Desalinated saltwater is a major source of potable water in
ther Zhoushan Archipelago in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Desalinization has also been introduced to the Xisha and Nansha
islands in the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
China ranks the sixth in the world in freshwater resources, but
has a per capita resource rate equal to only 25 percent of the
worldwide average. Over 300 Chinese cities currently face water
shortage, including 14 coastal cities facing severe shortages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
