<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Flies to Washington for Strategic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
left for Washington Thursday morning on a week-long visit to meet
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to initiate the
strategic dialog between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The meetings of the first strategic dialog between Egypt and
the U.S. will start on Friday, with a meeting between Moussa and
Albright before a plenary meeting of their two delegations,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sessions at experts' level will start later to discuss all
issues relating to Egyptian-American relations in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The strategic dialog between Egypt and the U.S. covers various
regional and international issues of joint interest, especially
Arab and African problems like the peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Washington, Moussa will meet with a number
of senior American officials, Congressmen and media men.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters here Wednesday that points of agreement
between Egypt and the U.S. are more than those of difference.
</P>
<P>
"The points of difference will be discussed during the upcoming
strategic dialog in Washington in a manner that helps open new
channels to forge greater understanding of the considerations
guiding the moves of each side," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa noted that Cairo and Washington see eye to eye on the
American initiative on reviving the Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks. The U.S. has proposed a 13.1 percent Israeli troops
withdrawal from the West Bank. It was rejected by Israel but
accepted by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss the unstable situation in a
number of African countries.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told an Egyptian Television program Wednesday that the
dialog would tackle not only the current bilateral economic
relationship, but also various spheres of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"It is not right for the dialog to be limited to the next five
or ten years of U.S. assistance to Egypt," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the foreign minister, like several other Egyptian ministers
who have visited Washington in the past few weeks, is most likely
to discuss how to use the U.S. economic aid to serve Egypt's
transformation into a market economy. The U.S. is considering
cutting this aid according to its policy of reducing foreign
economic aid.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, as the first Arab country to seal peace with Israel,
gets a total of 815 million U.S. dollars of economic aid every
year and 1.3 billion dollars military aid from the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
