<HEADLINE> Philippines to Recover Soon From Crisis: Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine central bank governor
Gabriel Singson Thursday predicted that the country will be among
the first to recover from the onslaught of the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the business sector's confidence in the present
government indicated that the country will be among the first to
bounce back from the financial crisis currently gripping the
region.
</P>
<P>
He said the business sector's confidence was shown by the
outcome of a dinner hosted by Metrobank Chairman George Ty
Wednesday night for President Joseph Estrada and some 350 leaders
of the local and foreign investment community.
</P>
<P>
"This is the opinion of many banks and analysts -- the
Philippines will be one of the, probably, two or three countries
that will get out of this turmoil ahead of the others," Singson
said.
</P>
<P>
Singson's forecast was shared by some economists working with
the Asian Development Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
The economists believed that the Philippines is the least affected
and has handled the financial crisis very well.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Singson said the favorable outlook shared by
financial analysts and local and foreign businessmen about the
Philippine economy will mean more investments and eventually the
rebound of the peso.
</P>
<P>
"If investments will come in, dollars will come in, then there
will be more dollars. And therefore, the peso will appreciate," he
said.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted among chief executives of
multinational companies in the Philippines showed that investors
were confident of the Estrada administration and the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who assumed the presidency on June 30 this year, has
vowed to create an economic environment conducive to free
competition and free from violence, crime and corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
