<HEADLINE> Qingdao Port to Handle 100 Million Tons of Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The completion of a new dock at the
end of this year is expected to make the port of Qingdao the next
Chinese port capable of handling 100 million tons of cargo a year,
following the ports of Shanghai and Qinhuangdao.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao, one of the country's oldest ports, now has an annual
handling capacity of 84.3 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The new ore dock now under construction, with an expected
annual capacity of 16 million tons, will be the largest in Asia
and the second largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Qingdao port has 14 docks and 70 berths, and trade
relations with more than 400 ports in 130 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
With advanced facilities and improved services, the port has
become the largest ore depot in northern China, the largest crude
oil depot, the second largest container shipping port, and the
fifth largest coal port in the whole of China.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the handling volume of the port reached 69.16 million
tons, rising at an annual rate of 20 percent over the past ten
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
