<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,200-Year-Old Pickaxe Found in Hubei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- An ancient iron pickaxe used for gold
excavation has been unearthed on a river bank in Shiyan City in
central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Three local farmers unexpectedly dug the pickaxe out of a sand
cave 10 meters beneath the earth working on the bank of the
Hanjiang River.
</P>
<P>
Local archeologists have determined that the pickaxe is at
least 2,200 years old.
</P>
<P>
The implement, 20 cm long, has a bent head, suitable for
working in narrow caves or ditches.
</P>
<P>
Located on the middle and upper reaches of the Hanjiang River,
this area has a long history as a gold-producing region, and there
are currently more than 20 gold-panning sites there.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists believe the discovery will be valuable for the
study of the development of gold extraction and the production of
iron tools in ancient times in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
