<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Loans to Help Poor People in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Thursday approved a package of 300 million U.S. dollars in loans
and nearly 3 million dollars in technical assistance grants to
help the poor in Indonesia who are hit by the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said in a press release that the
Indonesian government will use the money to develop a social
protection program to help school dropouts, poor pregnant women
and malnourished infants in the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis has pushed the cost of attending school and
obtaining essential health care beyond the reach of Indonesia's
poorest people. This jeopardizes their future productivity -- a
cost that Indonesia will have to bear for many years," said
Charles Currin, an ADB senior education specialist working on the
program.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to maintain the quality of social services for
the poor and reform the delivery of social services. It will also
promote decentralized management of social services, reduce
education costs for the poor and develop incentives for schools to
maintain enrollments and for village midwives to better assist
poor families.
</P>
<P>
The program will also provide scholarships for junior secondary
school students, support the rapidly increasing number of street
children and provide additional nutritious feeding for infants,
children and pregnant women, the press release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
