<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More American Women Have Infertility Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- As many as 7.7 million American
women may be infertile in the year 2025, according to a study
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by Elizabeth Hervey Stephen and Anjani
Chandr, and published in the July issue of Fertility and
Sterility, found there was a tendency of an increase in
infertility in the United States for the past 16 years.
</P>
<P>
There were 4.5 million U.S. women with infertility in 1982, and
the number grew to 4.9 million in 1988, and 6.2 million in 1995,
said the study, adding that infertility rates among American women
aged 15 to 44 increased to 10.2 percent in 1995 from 8 percent in
the earlier 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In addition to delayed childbearing, the increase in
infertility may be also due to "a larger percentage of women with
gonorrhea or chlamydial infection who have unrecognized and
presumably more serious cases of pelvic inflammatory disease,"
said the researchers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
