<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Ba People Relics Discovered in Three Gorges Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists from a
Northwest China university have recently discovered relics of the
ancient Ba people at Zhongbazi in the Three Gorges region of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The ancient Ba people are believed to have lived around the
Three Gorges and present-day Chongqing City about 3,000 to 4,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Archeological experts have known very little about the Ba
State.
</P>
<P>
The recently discovered site at Zhongbazi includes 20 pits and
two tombs.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, the pits dug by the Ba people were in
round and ellipse shapes and were used as rubbish heaps.
</P>
<P>
The tombs were built vertically, and many pots, spoons in the
shape of bird heads and earthen ware have been excavated from them.
</P>
<P>
Most of the pottery is red and grey with blue veins and designs
on them.
</P>
<P>
At this Ba site more than 1,000 pieces of stoneware have been
unearthed along with some bronze pieces.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, the excavated relics indicate that the
culture of the early Ba people was related to the culture of
western Sichuan Province and to the culture on the plain of the
Yangtze River and Hanjiang River in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Scholars have said that the Ba people enjoyed a diversity of
primitive activities involving fishing, hunting, farming and
animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
They added that this is the first large excavation of a Ba site
that promises to tell them more about the Ba people's living
conditions, agriculture and handicrafts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Announce New Transition Program Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is expected
to announce a new transition program soon as the country's ruling
body, the Provisional Ruling Council (PRC), may have completed a
meeting late Wednesday night to take a final decision.
</P>
<P>
PRC members and state administrators held a joint meeting in
the day time Wednesday in the capital Abuja, to discuss important
issues on the current political situation in the country,
according to Yobe State Administrator, Group Captain John
Benkanliu.
</P>
<P>
Benkanliu, spokesman for PRC, disclosed this at the end of
Wednesday's day-time meeting, which apparently did not reach
agreement on the expected new transition program.
</P>
<P>
The administrator was quoted by the state TV, the Nigerian
Television Authority (NTA), as saying that the meeting discussed
the consultations held by new leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar
on the way forward for the country's transition to civil rule
program.
</P>
<P>
He said the PRC was expected to meet later into the night to
take the final decision, adding that a statement will be issued
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The country's new Chief of General Staff, Rear Admiral Ikahai
Mike Akhigbe and new Chief of Defense Staff, Air-Vice Marshal
Alami Dagash were sworn in by Abubakar at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Akhigbe was appointed last Saturday to replace Lt.-Gen.
Oladipo Diya now in jail for alleged involvement in a coup plot
last December.
</P>
<P>
Dagash was named the same day to fill the gap left by Abubakar
after he became head of state immediately after late leader Sani
Abacha's death on June 8.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Abubakar ordered the dissolution of the
cabinet known as the Federal Executive Council, demanding that
all the ministries' work be in the charge of their permanent
secretaries until further notice.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now has come to a crossroads as the sudden death of
Abacha has left the transition program with no presidential
candidate less than two months before the election begins on
August 1 as originally planned.
</P>
<P>
Abacha was adopted by the country's five political parties in
April as their sole consensus presidential candidate not long
before his death.
</P>
<P>
The opposition groups had been demanding the cancellation of
the transition program and the establishment of a national unity
government to be headed by Abiola.
</P>
<P>
However, as the Abubakar government is holding a wide
consultation on the way to save Nigeria from its political
crisis, Abiola died Tuesday at the negotiation table, in the very
presence of a high-powered U.S. delegation who had come to secure
his release.
</P>
<P>
His death has sparked violence Tuesday night in such southern
cities as Lagos and Ibadan, where most of Abiola's supporters and
sympathizers live.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that the only option now open to the
government is an extension of the transition program, by a period
of one year at the most, as indicated by views forwarded during
the consultations.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear at the moment whether the government will
merely shift the presidential election or start a whole new
transition program, which means all the parties will be dissolved
and previous elections canceled, as have been suggested by some
sectors of the society.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, do believe that in either case, the
transition period will not last longer than one year, which seems
to be a deadline acceptable to both Nigerians and the
international society.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Population Grows Fastest in Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's population is increasing at
the highest rate in the Arab world, expected to reach 7.1 million
by 2010, the Jordan Times daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's annual population growth rate stands at 4.4 percent,
Jordanian Minister of Labor Mohammed Mehdi Farhan Wednesday told a
press conference marking the World Population Day.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom's population has increased by eight folds since
1952, which is an "extraordinary and forced growth" related to
political, economic and demographic changes, Farhan, who also
heads the National Population Commission, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the Jordanians are more aware of the need to
control population growth naturally in order to improve the
standard of living," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's high population growth rate is caused by forced
migration due to the 1990 Gulf crisis, long life expectancy,
reduced infant mortality, lack of contraception and high fertility
rate, according to a recent government press release.
</P>
<P>
Due to Jordan's support for Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
tens of thousands of Jordanian workers in Gulf Arab countries were
forced to return home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
