<HEADLINE> Vietnam Plans to Help People in Poor Communes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
recently introduced a project to help people in the poor communes,
Vietnamese News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project, which combines family planning with economic
development, is mainly aimed at reducing the proportion of couples
with three children or more, and increasing the number of
contraceptive users by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, women aged between 15-49 and their husbands
will have access to information on family planning, contraceptive
methods, and ways to care for babies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will also improve the living
conditions, education and health care services of the people in
poor communes by providing loans and farming techniques.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has allocated 560 billion Vietnamese
dong (about 43 million U.S. dollars) to assist poor communes this
year.
</P>
<P>
The project will be carried out in 40 communes this year, 300
communes in 1999, and 500 communes by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,700 out of 10,300 communes and wards in Vietnam are
classified as poor communes, which are home mostly to people of
ethnic minority groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
