<HEADLINE> Tourism Booms in "Silk Road" City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Dunhuang in northwest China's
Gansu Province, a famous city on the ancient Silk Road, is
rapidly becoming ideal destination for an increasing number of
Chinese and overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that the city hosted over 62,000
tourists during the first six months of this year, up 21.13 percent
on the 1997 period. The figure included 7,821 foreign tourists, or
50 percent more than in last year's same period.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang earned 15.56 million yuan from tourism during the
January-June period this year, up 26.8 percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The city is home to 241 cultural relics under state protection,
including the Mogao Grottoes which are famous for murals and
natural scenic beauty.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang has reinforced construction of tourism facilities over
the past decade and now has 105 hotels and restaurants, with
nearly 8,000 beds. The city's tourism sector currently employs
some 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Well over a million Japanese citizens have either visited or
expressed interest in visiting Dunhuang, which has also attracted
an increasing number of Europeans and Americans in recent years.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
