<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Introduces Fingerprint Identification Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Compaq Computer Corp., the
world's largest personal computer-maker, has unveiled its
Fingerprint Identification Technology, a way to use a person's
fingerprint instead of a password to log into a computer network,
reports from the company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The product is expected to become available next month and
widespread in three or five years, according to Tim Bajarin,
president of the Creative Strategies, an industry research firm.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said the new technology uses a device, about
the size of a deck of cards, which plugs into the office
computer. A camera takes a picture of a person's fingerprint, and
the software transforms the fingerprint into a point map that is
stored for future reference, they explained.
</P>
<P>
Later, a user holds a finger to the camera, and the computer
matches the stored print map to the fingerprint.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts noted that products similar to Compaq's have
already been on the market. What is new is that Compaq's product
will sale for 99 U.S. dollars, compared with 199 dollars paid for
the similar product from Biometric Access Corp, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Strives to Develop Power Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's power sector grew by 6.4
percent in output value in the 1997-98 fiscal year over the
previous one.
</P>
<P>
The installed generating capacity of the state-owned Myanmar
Electric Power Enterprise (MEPE), the main electricity supplier in
the country, was 1,207 megawatts (mw) in the fiscal year ending
March, compared with 1,031 mw in the previous year, according to
an official report on the country's financial, economic and social
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The MEPE thus accounted for 77 percent of the country's total
installed generating capacity and it generated 4.2 billion
kilowatt-hours (kwh) of electricity in fiscal 1997-98, 260 million
kwh more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total generated power, 2.3 billion kwh or 55 percent was
produced by natural gas and 1.6 billion kwh or 39 percent by
hydropower, indicating that natural gas dominates power
generation.
</P>
<P>
The power consumption of the country increased to 2.5 billion
kwh, a rise of 130 million kwh over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total consumption, 1.1 billion kwh or 45 percent was for
domestic use, 919 million kwh or 37 percent for industrial
utilization and the rest 18 percent for public buildings and
others.
</P>
<P>
The MEPE also extended power transmission and distribution
lines to 21,458 kilometers in the 1997-98 fiscal year, 552
kilometers longer than the previous year, bringing electricity to
323 towns and 1,087 villages.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increase in power generation, electricity supply is
still far from meeting the country's demand as the economy is
developing with more involvement of the private sector and foreign
 investors.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the power shortage, especially in the capital of
Yangon where industry is under development, the authorities have
urged the public to cut down the use of electricity. They said
some power stations in the country have to reduce their production
in view of two consecutive years of scarcity of rain in northern
Myanmar and the falling water level of dams.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the authorities are expected to take measures to
meet the power demand such as exploring hydroelectric power
potentials to increase installed capacity, expanding natural-gas
power generating plants and setting up power distribution joint
ventures or solely-owned companies by local and foreign
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has built three hydropower stations and three
natural-gas power stations since 1988. Feasibility studies on
building more are under way by companies from Japan, the Republic
of Korea, China and some other multinational developer groups.
</P>
<P>
In power transmission and distribution, Myanmar has initiated a
first joint-venture contract with a Malaysian company during the
fiscal year, with three South Korean firms offering assistance.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's power sector contributed 1 percent of the gross
domestic product in 1997-98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0237 </DOCNO>
