<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 07:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Million Babies Born Unregistered Annually in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- About 40 million babies, or one third
of the births in the world, are born unregistered annually due to
national and regional turmoils, leaving them in unfavorable
conditions, according to a U.N. report released here.
</P>
<P>
"Every day, the right to nationality is jeopardized for
millions of children born in countries undergoing political
turmoil," Jordanian Queen Noor told the closing ceremony of the
18th Arab Children's Congress on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Noor was commissioned to deliver the report of the United
Nations Children's Fund on progress of nations in 1998 at the
conference, the semi-official Jordan Times Daily said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In many countries, a child without proof of birth can not be
vaccinated, treated at a health center or enrolled in school, the
Jordanian queen said.
</P>
<P>
Each year, 2 million children die from vaccine-preventable
diseases and the sustainability of immunization is now threatened
by the increase of the unregistered babies, though child
immunization rate in developing countries has increased from 5
percent in 1980 to nearly 80 percent these days, Noor said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's birth registration rate stands at 90 percent, primary
school enrollment rate reaches 92 percent and the immunization
rates for polio and measles are both over 90 percent, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
