<HEADLINE> China Implements Reemployment Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Government at various levels and
various trade sectors throughout China are introducing effective
measures to create new job opportunities for laid-off workers,
according to today's People's Daily, China's leading national
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Shaanxi Province had helped 140,000
unemployed workers find new jobs by the end of May this year, with
over 60 percent of related individuals working in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
The provincial industrial and commercial bureau has granted
business licenses to 20,000 unemployed people.
</P>
<P>
The labor bureau in Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang
Province, has pledged to provide jobs for each and every applicant
willing to do any work. The city has offered jobs to 75,000
unemployed people since July 1995.
</P>
<P>
Over 30,000 workers, or 70 percent of the total number of
people laid-off in Ganzhou, Jiangxi Province, have found new jobs
thanks to a series of preferential measures adopted by the local
government.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises in the power generation sector provided jobs for
some 820,000 workers by the end of 1997. As a result, the net
operational profits for the sector, excluding power generation
revenues, has averaged four billion yuan annually over the past
few years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
