<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang Expands Border Trade with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Heilongjiang, China's northernmost
Province which shares an over 3,000 km border with Russia, plans
to adopt flexible policies to encourage Chinese enterprises to
process or export goods in great demand on the Russian market,
according to the overseas edition of today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Vice Governor Wang Zhenchuan said the provincial
government plans to open more ports of entry and simplify
procedures to promote direct trade between China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to consolidate traditional markets in
eastern Europe, Hong Kong, Macao and the Commonwealth of
Independent States, while opening new markets in Africa and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will establish free trade zones and develop
diversified border trade in order to enhance bilateral economic
and trade contacts, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang has forged trade ties with 140 countries and
regions and the province reported border trade worth 12.5 billion
U.S. dollars by the end of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
