<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Neighborhood Committees Assist Laid-Off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 150,000 laid-off workers in
northeast China's Liaoning Province are expected to find new jobs
this year with the help of the province's urban neighborhood
committees,
</P>
<P>
The province recently issued a circular introducing an
extensive campaign of select advanced urban neighborhood
committees which are responsible for helping laid-off workers find
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Chinese workers declared redundant by enterprises are paying
increasing attention to economic efficiency required by the market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The central government and various social organizations such as
trade unions, women's federations and the Communist Youth League
organizations have spared no effort to help laid-off workers find
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning, an old heavy industrial base established under the
planned economy, is home to 10 percent of China's medium to large
state enterprises. Some 1.2 million workers, including 800,000
workers currently employed by state-owned enterprises, will loose
their jobs over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning helped 1.236 million unemployed people, including
workers laid off by enterprises, find new jobs between
1994-1997. The province plans to help an additional 400,000
unemployed people find new jobs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Urban neighborhood committees maintain close contacts with
Chinese urbanites and their efforts to help unemployed workers
find new jobs as quickly as possible will undoubtedly contribute
to ensuring a stable society, according to an official from the
Liaoning Labor Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He cited the Tiexi District in Shenyang, the provincial
capital, as a prime example. He pointed out that the district's
445 neighborhood committees have opened 4,628 service centers
which have created over 8,000 new job opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
