<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Exchange Turnover at 31.2 BLN Dollars in Jan.-Jun. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The turnover on the Shanghai
national foreign exchange market hit 31.27 billion US dollars for
the first half of the year, according to statistics released by
the China Foreign Exchange Trading System.
</P>
<P>
The volume represented a daily trade volume of 252 million US
dollars during the January-June period. A further breakdown reveals
that trade involved 29.2 billion US dollars, 13.1 billion Hong
Kong dollars, and 43 billion Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
US dollars accounted for 94 percent of the period transaction
volume, with the Hong Kong dollar accounting for five percent and
Japanese currency one percent.
</P>
<P>
US dollar exchange rates during the period ranged from 8.779 to
8.2800 yuan Renminbi. The rate on June 30, the final trading day for
the first half of the year, closed at 8.2797 yuan, a level which
was essentially unchanged from the 1997 closing rate of 8.2796
yuan a dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar exchange rate against the yuan edged down
by a small margin during the period to end at 1.0683 yuan on June
30, compared with 1.0699 yuan at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen gained ground on the Chinese currency at the
beginning of the year, but declined in ensuring months. The June
30 average-weighted value for Japanese currency stood at 5.8737
yuan per 100 yen, down from 6.3525 yuan at the end of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inter-Bank Interest Rates Drop in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The average inter-bank interest
rates in the money market dropped last week to 20,66 percent from
29.10 percent in the previous week, the Central Bank of Kenya
(CBK) says.
</P>
<P>
The CBK data issued Wednesday showed that the rate moved from
25.67 percent at the beginning of the week on June 29 to 18.30
percent last week, an indication of increased liquidity in the
market.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate for the 91-day Treasury bill fell further to
24.92 percent last week, compared to 25.12 percent in the
previous auction.
</P>
<P>
The CBK Chief Economist, Maurice Kanga, said that as a result
of a general decline in interest rates, a number of commercial
banks had lowered their base lending rates resulting in a
reduction in the overall average rate to 27.8 percent from 27.97
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Shilling remained strong against the hard
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The average exchange rate against the U.S. Dollars was 59.43
while against the Sterling Pound, the Shilling traded a 98.34
Shillings compared to 59.50 Shillings and 99.26 Shillings
respectively in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources said the market was expected to remain at
about the same levels throughout the week as market players look
for new factors to influence the level of the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"However, dividend payments from corporates towards the end of
the month (July) may ignite some reaction and put pressure on the
local unit," dealers said.
</P>
<P>
A weekend report by Loita Asset Management said the onset of
the new cash ratio requirement saw interest rates fall to around
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the reduction of the cash ratio from 15
percent to 14 percent which commences on July 15 should see
increased liquidity for banks and also ease interbank rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
