<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Blames MILF Rebels for Skirmishes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine army has blamed the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front's (MILF) "loose control" over its
men as the reason behind the clashes between the two sides in
Buldon of Maguindanao Province, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Major Rosque Garingalao, spokesman of the army's Sixth Infantry
Division in the south, said Thursday that the MILF usually starts
"trouble" in Buldon by launching small-scale harassment on
military detachments which later would balloon to intense levels.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that despite the continuous sporadic
skirmishes, the army remains optimistic that ongoing talks between
the government and the MILF will eventually succeed.
</P>
<P>
He said for its part, the national government has continuously
been implementing development projects in Camp Abubakar, the
MILF's biggest base in Mindanao, "for confidence-building
measures."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Garingalao said, all the soldiers have been ordered
to strictly abide by the ground rules of a cease-fire agreement
both parties signed in April last year.
</P>
<P>
"Every soldier has been ordered to strictly respect the
cease-fire agreement." he said.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Murad, MILF vice-military chief meanwhile expressed joy
over the army's announcement to obey the truce agreement, but
denied that the MILF forces started animosities in Buldon in the
past.
</P>
<P>
"Not one, I could not remember of a case where our men started
any trouble," he said. He urged the military to monitor whether or
not the cessation order is really being implemented by its men in
the field.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the largest rebel group in the
Philippines. The 12,000-strong insurgency group has been engaged
in low-level talks with the government during the past few years,
but has made little progress in reaching a final peace agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
