<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-hit Province Organizes Relief Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province,
which is suffering from serious flooding, is organizing relief
efforts to alleviate effects of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
By now, floods have affected 500,000 hectares of crops and left
320,000 head of livestock dead. And the situation is worsening,
especially in the Dongting Lake area where the water level is
still rising, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government called on local residents to re-plant
crops, such as rice, and develop diversified undertakings while
fighting floods in an effort to increase farmers' income despite
the calamity.
</P>
<P>
Local agricultural departments have organized 10 relief groups
and sent them to flood-stricken areas to help farmers with
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
One of the measures taken by the province to restore rice
production was to secure a late rice acreage of about 1.86 million
hectares, a significant increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Related departments are providing seeds, epidemic prevention
and information services to farmers. In addition, they are
encouraging farmers to raise pigs, poultry and fish to earn extra
money.
</P>
<P>
The city of Changsha, the provincial capital, has shipped in
maize seeds from elsewhere, and sold them to farmers at a lower
price to replant 2,000 hectares of maize. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
