<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Garments, Textile Exports Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's number-one foreign
exchange earner, the textile and apparel industry, earned 692.3
million U.S. dollars in the first four months this year, an
increase of 18 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Apparel Exporters Association
Thursday, the industry's export earnings had increased by 10
percent in dollar terms. The sources estimated that the industry
will grow by 15 to 20 percent during this year.
</P>
<P>
The industry earned 2.18 billion U.S. dollars from exports last
year, a 38-percent growth over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken a number of measures to develop the
industry during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Sri Lanka is unlikely to face competition
following the devaluation of currencies in several countries in
the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's garment manufacturers are moving toward quotaless
markets which is a good indication of the strength of the local
garment industry.
</P>
<P>
The government is encouraging local industrialists to produce
fabrics and other raw materials for the industry. This move will
be help save a large amount of foreign exchange now being spent on
these imports, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The industry provides direct employment to more than 350,000
people at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
