<HEADLINE> Thai PM Urges Cabinet to Improve PR Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai,
reacting to negative coverage of Thailand by foreign media, has
urged his cabinet members to do a better public relations job, the
Nation newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan's reaction came after the Reuters and Agence
France-Presse news agencies issued bleak economic analyses and
reports about Thailand a year after the economy began its plummet,
The newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister issued the instruction at Tuesday's cabinet
meeting during which the Public Relations Department submitted a
report on the foreign media's coverage of Thailand over the past
few months.
</P>
<P>
The department said Western news agencies are of the opinion
that prospects for a revival are not bright, citing concerns
ranging from political and social issues to financial instability.
</P>
<P>
The Public Relations Department, which monitors foreign media
coverage, said the reports are affecting the confidence of foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
The department suggested that the government continue to make
efforts to boost foreign confidence in the country's political
system and economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
