<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Becomes Job-Search Tool in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Hewlett-Packard(HP), a computer
maker based in California, hired 1,000 people from Web
applications last year.
</P>
<P>
The number was a significant portion of HP's total hires, said
the Internet hiring leader which employs 123,000 people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
HP is not alone in using Internet as a recruiting tool. In
fact, the information superhighway is becoming the American way to
employment. Hiring advertisements, resumes, job listings, training
sessions and notices of career fairs and workshops are
continuously shooting through cyberspace. On-line observers
estimate Internet job postings more than doubled this year in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Many companies and organizations offer on-line application
forms on their Web sites, usually under the entry of "employment."
</P>
<P>
HP's home page offers detailed job description, minimum and
desired qualifications for a certain job, so that applicants can
measure themselves in terms of their interest, background and
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Under R&AMP;D, for instance, hardware design engineer, software
design engineer and firmware design engineer are listed as job
titles, and each has a digital code seemingly for relevant
managers to easily pickup their needed applicants.
</P>
<P>
The Internet is the only way to get some jobs, such as soft
ware and network engineering positions. A great variety of job
seekers uses CareerMosaic to access the site's 70,000 job
listings. Apart from high-tech and tech-oriented jobs, the site
places short-order cooks, health care workers, financial planners
and box packers. The site averages 450,000 hits a day.
</P>
<P>
A month-long CareerMosaic ad cost only 160 U.S. dollars, while
other forms of advertising might run as high as 8,000 dollars a
day.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, even people without PCs use the Internet to search
for jobs. The growth of terminals at libraries, cybercafes and
schools encourages public access. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
