<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Laid-off Women Find New Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- About three quarters of Beijing's
laid-off women have obtained new jobs in the past two years,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Latest survey conducted by the Beijing Women's Federation found
that 67,000 recently laid-off women -- 76 percent of the total --
and 22,000 previously unemployed women -- about two thirds of the
total -- have found new jobs. Those who had worked for the State
received unemployment benefits.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the 197,000 employees laid-off or sacked in
the capital last years were women.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Yarong, director of the Women's Right Department of
Beijing Women's Federation, is quoted as saying that China's women
wokers had a harder time than men under the country's economic
restructuring and the reform of State-owned enterprises because
they often held low-skill jobs in hard-hit industries such as
textiles.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the problem, the department set up a service center
for unemployed women two years ago. Since then, the center and
district branches throughout the city have provided vocational
training and job information to more than 20,000 women. Over 3,000
found new jobs with their help.
</P>
<P>
Most found jobs in their communities, including working as
domestics.
</P>
<P>
"Most laid-off women workers have changed their mentality,
which has made our work much easier than before," Zhou said. But
there is a new problem, protecting women's rights at their new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Many of them are assigned to short-term jobs with little job
security, and more and more contract disputes have appeared
recently, Zhou added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
