<HEADLINE> SriLanka to Launch First Wind Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's first wind power
project will be launched Thursday in Hambantota, about 130 km
south of Colombo, according to the Power and Energy Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3.9 million U.S. dollars will be spent on the
project which is expected to add a generation capacity of three
megawatts to the national electricity grid by April next year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign cost of the project will be financed by a soft loan
from the International Development Association of the World Bank
and a grant from the Global Environment Facility, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
There is a potential for wind power in Sri Lanka's south
eastern coastal belt to supply over 200 megawatt-hours of
electricity.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the government, while looking seriously into
the possibility of creating a feasible balance between the hydro
and thermal generation capacity in the country, also hopes to
speed up the development of wind power. 
</P>
