<HEADLINE> Car Sales Drop Sharply in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Passenger car sales in the first
half of this year dropped 50.6 percent to 20,036 units from the
year-ago level as a result of the currency crisis and a credit
crunch, the Business World reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said sales in June were only 2,888 units, a
56.6-percent drop compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Car assemblers are not so upbeat that the sales trend will
improve in the second half even as most continue their promotion
activities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"A 30 percent reduction in total sales this year (compared with
1997) will already be good enough," Toyota Motors Phils.
Corporation Executive Vice President Florencio Jurado said.
</P>
<P>
The assemblers have attributed the sales trend to the reduction
of the customers' purchasing power due to the ongoing Asian
financial crisis and the credit crunch by banks to the mobile
industry.
</P>
<P>
Jurado said the trend is expected not only in the Philippines
but in some other Asian countries as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
