<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> La Nina Phenomenon to Affect Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will experience a wet dry
season during the next one to two months as a result of the La
Nina phenomenon, the opposite of El Nino, the Antara News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Clouded skies and drizzles with a small amount of rainfall
would characterize the wet dry season, the report quoted Heri
Haryanto, head of the Meteorological and Geophysical Agency's
Analysis Division, as saying.
</P>
<P>
If the La Nina phenomenon would last longer than one to two
months, there are reasons for concern because a large
precipitation could be expected to occur in the August-December
period and eventually cause floods, he said.
</P>
<P>
La Nina is the reverse of the El Nino effect and is associated
with colder-than-normal surface temperatures in the eastern
Pacific Ocean. The El Nino effect, which is said to be the most
severe in 50 years, aggravated forest fires in Indonesia's Sumatra
and Kalimantan Islands last year. Over 5 million hectares of
forest were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
According to the July 1998 weather evaluation and forecast,
since early last month there has been a shift in the global
weather from the El Nino phenomenon to the La Nina phenomenon in
the form of a decline in temperature which would last until March
1999, Haryanto said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Public Telephone Sets in Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The increase of public telephone sets
in Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, offers local
residents more access to modern communications and opens a market
potential for businessmen, according to officials with the Lhasa
Bureau of Posts and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
In the streets of Lhasa, whenever a pedestrian receives a
beeper call, a nearby telephone booth will be available, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
A businessman named Jiang said after he opened his telephone
booth, a dozen neighboring shopkeepers gave up their plan of
telephone subscription.
</P>
<P>
"My telephone booth gets even more business on weekends or on
public holidays, and more than 100 telephone calls can be made on
a Sunday," he said.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 130,000, Lhasa has 950 public telephone
sets, and there is a public telephone available every 100 meters
in the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
Public telephone booths began to appear in Lhasa in 1992. In
the following three years, the local telecommunications bureau
adopted preferential policies such as free telephone installation
to encourage urban residents to have public telephone booths.
</P>
<P>
The increased living standard also has boosted the expansion of
telephone service. The local government has poured several billion
yuan into telecommunications construction in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show there are 2.41 telephone sets for every 100
people in the region, and 23.56 telephone sets for every 100
people in Lhasa city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
