<HEADLINE> Workers Need Updated Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Technicians laid off from
state-owned firms are ready to take on new jobs after acquiring
updated, higher-level skills, a senior scientific official said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Association for Science and Technology (CAST) will
serve as the link helping technicians to find new jobs, Zhou
Guangzhao, president of the association and also vice-chairman of
the Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress,
was cited by today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
CAST, the largest non-governmental organization focusing on the
dissemination of science and technology, is well known as "the
home of scientists and technicians".
</P>
<P>
"Laid-off technicians are still an important component part of
the country's scientific teams. Science and technology
associations across the country will provide them with more
employment information," said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
Some of dozens of regional science and technology associations
from all over the country have taken steps to give higher-level
professional training to those laid-off.
</P>
<P>
For example, in Hebei Province, Haiyan Secondary Technical
School provides free training for laid-off workers. The school has
trained 6,800 unemployment workers in maintenance skills for
household electrical appliances, who provide useful services for
local residents.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent CAST survey, the 403 State-owned firms
surveyed employ 223,000 technicians. Some 11,000, or 4.9 percent
of them, have been laid off. And 90 percent of those laid-off are
workers with low technical skills, the survey has indicated.
</P>
