<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Enhances Int'l Cooperation in Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Chongqing
Municipality has increased international cooperation in
environmental protection and the effort is beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in the early 1990s, Chongqing arranged coorperation
with foreign environmental businesses and research institutions by
way of importing their technologies and expertise.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the city launched a project to treat industrial
pollution and reorganize businesses with the aid of a World Bank
loan of 170 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing environmental experts, World Bank officials and
scientists from the United States and Britain have now begun to
study air quality, solid waste and industrial waste water in the
city.
</P>
<P>
The city was also granted a 250 million US dollar loan from the
World Bank for improving the urban environment. This includes
building a sewage treatment plant, a running water plant and
underground water network and garbage treatment facilities.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing's air pollution and acid rain problems are among the
most serious in the world. Five years ago, the Japanese city of
Hiroshima set up a research center to monitor acid rain. As a
result, Chongqing will receive 100 million US dollars in loans
from Japan for air pollution control over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
In addition,Chongqing has signed contracts with foreign cities
on environment-related training programs, desulphurization, noise
control and water pollution control for sections of the Yangtze
and Jialing rivers.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the city's air quality will meet state-set
standards sometime early in the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
