<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pakistan Govt Faces Uphill Task of Ending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government is
facing an uphill task of restoring peace and harmony in the
southern port city of Karachi where people have been living in a
nightmare of murders and bomb blasts for a long time.
</P>
<P>
According to figures in the Pakistani press, as many as 3,598
people have been killed in the past three years as a result of
violence in Karachi, the commercial and industrial center of this
South Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
In June this year alone, a renewed wave of violence claimed 178
lives, an average of six killings each day.
</P>
<P>
"The deteriorating law and order has stifled the economic
growth of the country," said Muhammad Hanif Janoo, president of
the Karachi Chamber of Commerce and Industries, shortly after
former minister Zuhair Akram Nadeem was shot dead by a group of
unidentified gunmen on July 4 in the violence-plagued city.
</P>
<P>
Contributing about 20 percent of the national gross domestic
product, 40 percent of the federal tax revenues and 80 percent of
the provincial tax revenues, the Sindh provincial capital with a
population of 12 million is the economic engine and commercial
lifeline of Pakistan, which is striving for its economic revival.
</P>
<P>
However, violence has paralyzed the city. People keep staying
at home as much as possible and many shops, markets and commercial
centers frequently shut down because of terrorist acts, causing
huge losses to businessmen and damaging the trade and investment
environment of the whole country.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that the economic price Pakistan is paying
for Karachi's uncontrollable drift will rise as time passes. The
government should take swift action before it is too late, they
warned.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that much of the unrest in Karachi is attributed
to the growing feud between the two rival factions within the
Muhajir Qaumi Movement (MQM) led respectively by Altaf Hussain
(MQM-A) and Afaq Ahmed (MQM-H), although differences among
political, religious, sectarian and ethnic groups in the city also
result in various kinds of violence.
</P>
<P>
According to police, many of the deaths as a result of the
violence in Karachi were linked to the lingering conflict between
the two MQM factions.
</P>
<P>
Occupying 28 seats in the 109-member Sindh Assembly in contrast
to the 14 held by the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (PML-N) led by
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the MQM is now a major partner of the
PML-N in the provincial coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Since the PML-N government took power in February, 1997, the
MQM has asked for withdrawal of cases against "innocent" MQM
workers, and demanded punishment of those involved in judicial
killings of MQM workers and compensation to the families of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
Trying to keep its alliance with the MQM in the Sindh
government, the PML-N government has vowed to take steps to end
terrorist activities in Karachi and bring peace back to the city.
</P>
<P>
Following a series of official meetings for charting a strategy
to counter the growing violence, the Sindh government was given a
free hand to deal with the deteriorating law and order situation
and a six-member committee headed by Sindh Chief Minister Liaquat
Ali Jatoi was set up.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government announced sweeping powers for
the 5,800 paramilitary rangers deployed in the mega city.
</P>
<P>
Under the powers, the paramilitary troops will carry out raids
and arrest suspects jointly with police in troubled areas of the
city.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that with the reinforcement and augmentation of
the police and by posting out good officers, the situation in the
city would improve.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the government has moved to resolve some
matters relating to the MQM. In January this year, for example,
the government withdrew non-bailable arrest warrants issued in
1995 against Altaf Hussain in connection with the murder of two
Americans.
</P>
<P>
All cases against 500 MQM activists have also been withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Cases Review Committee with the MQM representation
has been set up which meets regularly to review cases filed
against the MQM.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the government's political will and
determination play a key role in restoring peace and harmony in
Karachi.
</P>
<P>
While firm and effective administrative measures are needed to
crush terrorists in the city, comprehensive talks should also be
undertaken to find a political solution to the festering problem,
they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
