<HEADLINE> North China Province Manufacturing Medicines For Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Tanzanian pharmaceutical
joint venture is expected to become operational and go into
operation by the end of the year, a Tanzanian economic and trade
delegation reported recently.
</P>
<P>
The joint Tanzania-China Pharmaceutical Factory will be set up
at a cost of 2.56 million U.S. dollars and will be run by the New
Technological Applications Center of north China's Shanxi
Province, with the Chinese partner holding 55 percent of the
shares and the Tanzanians, 45 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture's products will be exported mainly to
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
