<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A symposium for leading officials of large state-owned
enterprises closed here Wednesday. Hu Jintao, a member of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) Central Committee and president of the Party School
of the CPC Central Committee, attended the closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
During the one-month symposium, participants studied the Deng
Xiaoping Theory, the report by General Secretary Jiang Zemin at
the Party's 15th CPC National Congress and a series of important
Party and government documents on state-owned enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
-- A growing number of enterprise lay-off workers nationwide
now find new jobs thanks to the efforts made by central and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
The governments has set up a lot of labor markets to open up
re-employment channels for more laid-off workers. At the same
time, related departments have formed a variety of social security
organizations to support the workers' basic life costs.
</P>
<P>
-- China's national industrial value grew by 176 billion yuan
this June, a 7.9 percent rise over the same month last year,
maintaining the same growth rate as the previous month, according
to the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A nationwide campaign has been launched to scrutinize the
conduct of China's 20,000 leading officials working at county- and
city-level procuratorates and anti-corruption bureaus.
</P>
<P>
"The major target will be focused on chief prosecutors and heads
of anti-corruption bureaus," according to a circular distributed
during a national tele-conference yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- The CPC Central Commission for Discipline Inspection
circulated a report by the CPC Heilongjiang Provincial Commission
for Disciple Inspection on a report concerning the Expulsion from
the Party of Zhu Shengwen, former vice-mayor of Harbin, capital of
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, for economic crimes.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China urged its trading partners yesterday to adopt a
"flexible" attitude in the upcoming Geneva talks on its entry into
the World Trade Organization. (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"We will do our best to open our market, but the other parties
concerned should also be pragmatic," said a Chinese government
official who declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
-- The scheduled visit of Koo Chen-fu, chairman of the Taipei
based Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), to the mainland this
autumn will be of little political significance unless Taiwan
makes a positive response to the mainland's proposals, a top
negotiator said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The SEF and its mainland counterpart, the Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) reached consensus late
last month on inviting Koo to visit the mainland in mid-September
or mid-October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
