<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> INTERPOL Calls Conference on Car Theft Insurance Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 30 countries will join an
international conference on insurance fraud and car theft in
Sofia, Bulgaria in September, a representative of the
International Criminal Police Organization (INTERPOL) said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hans Faleneger, of the General Secretariat of INTERPOL, said
the European Union, the United States and Canada will attend the
conference organized by INTERPOL and the Bulgarian government.
</P>
<P>
Leading world insurance agencies and insurers' associations are
also expected to attend, Faleneger said.
</P>
<P>
He said every year about 1.5 million to 1.6 million automobiles
are stolen in the EU, half of them just disappearing forever.
</P>
<P>
It is very difficult to detect stolen cars subject to insurance
fraud, he said. This was because an owner may sell a car to
traffickers and then report the "theft" to the local police.
</P>
<P>
In some countries such an owner is paid the insurance indemnity
within one month, he said.
</P>
<P>
Large insurance agencies have smoothly running machinery for
tracing such cars. Problems still exist, however, as the domestic
legislation of certain countries recognizes the status of an
innocent purchaser.
</P>
<P>
Faleneger said INTERPOL decided to hold the conference in Sofia
because it appreciated the government's efforts and cooperation
with the organization to counter car theft.
</P>
<P>
Since December 1 last year, all used cars imported into
Bulgaria have been mandatorily checked against the wanted list,
and INTERPOL gives positive marks to the action by Sofia,
Faleneger said.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria also is one of 22 countries which have given
INTERPOL access to its data base on stolen automobiles, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia's Yellow River Area Producing More Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The irrigated area at the great bend
of the Yellow River in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region has become a "three-high" agricultural demonstration zone
as a result of the implementation of a comprehensive agricultural
development program.
</P>
<P>
Three-high agriculture features high output, high quality and
high efficiency, qualities which have been heralded as the future
of China's agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
Some 73,000 hectares of land have been upgraded or reclaimed
for farming since the comprehensive agricultural development
program was first launched in 1992, according to the Comprehensive
Agricultural Development Office of the Bayannur League, the
organization responsible for the irrigated area at the great bend
of the Yellow River, commonly known as the Hetao Area.
</P>
<P>
According to authorities, the output of grain, oil and sugar
for consumption of one cu m of water has gone up from 0.0175 kg
six years ago to the present 0.56 kg.  The total output of grain
and legumes has also increased from 71 million kg six years ago to
the present 1.5 billion kg.
</P>
<P>
Under the comprehensive agricultural development program, more
irrigation and drainage works have been built along 330,000
hectares of farmland to facilitate efficient irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Some 66 million U.S. dollars worth of loans from the World Bank
have been used to finance a project designed to build
supporting facilities in the Hetao area. This investment has helped
construct irrigation systems and drainage works along 200,000
hectares of farmland, improved 39,000 hectares of alkaline land
and upgraded 54,000 hectares of low-yield land.
</P>
<P>
While intensifying water management, the Hetao area has also
utilized many advanced water-efficient technologies over 27,000
hectares of farmland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two East China Provinces to Construct Expressway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The east China provinces of
Zhejiang and Jiangsu have announced plans to jointly construct an
expressway linking Jiaxing's Zhapu Port in the former with Suzhou
in the latter.
</P>
<P>
Construction will begin in April 1999 and the project will be
completed at a projected cost of 1.93 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
An official from Zhapu Development Zone said the expressway
will promote construction of the port and provide a convenient
transportation channel for areas in southern Jiangsu.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing-Shanghai Expressway has opened traffic in the
Yangtze River Delta and construction on the
Shanghai-Hangzhou-Ningbo Expressway is proceeding smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Zhapu Port is located on the northern shores of Hangzhou Bay in
the Yangtze Delta some 100 km distant from Shanghai, Hangzhou,
Suzhou and Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
The port has seven berths in operation and plans to increase
its annual handling capacity to 50 million tons by the year
2010. Zhapu is expected to become a major component of the
Shanghai international transportation hub. 
</P>
</TEXT>
