<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Mobile Hospital Helps Poor People Regain Eyesight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Maomao had lived in darkness since
he was born two years ago. That was when a train equipped with
state-of-the-art medical equipment arrived in his hometown in east
China's Fujian Province and he underwent eye surgery free of
charge.
</P>
<P>
When Maomao gained his sight, the first thing he saw was the
bright rainbow painted on the train -- the Lifeline Express from
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The mobile eye hospital, which was made possible by donations
from Hong Kong residents, became operational on July 1, 1997. Its
doctors have performed cataract removal operations for 2,000
people in poor areas of the Chinese inland provinces of Anhui,
Sichuan, Hubei and Fujian.
</P>
<P>
Apart from eye surgery, doctors on the Lifeline Express also
provide treatment to people with polio, give health advice to
local people and help train local medical personnel, according to
sources with the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Some social groups and charity funds in Hong Kong are
considering donating a second mobile hospital to give more poor
people access to free medical treatment, the sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
