<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Measures to Ensure Grain Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has taken
a series of measures to maintain farmers' enthusiasm in growing
grain though the country has achieved grain harvest goals for
three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
This is important for an agricultural state which has to feed a
population of 1.2 billion, 22 percent of the world's total, with
its one-seventh of the farmland on earth, said an agricultural
expert.
</P>
<P>
The government has set a minimum purchase price for summer
grain this year in a bid to prevent farmers' losses in the wake of
successive harvests. It will bring an additional income of 2-to-3
billion yuan to farmers in central China's Henan Province, a major
wheat producer in China.
</P>
<P>
Leading grain-producing areas including Shandong, Henan and
Hebei provinces have encouraged farmers to adopt intercropping and
apply more modern agro-techniques, which have been proved to
increase the multiple-crop area by 170-to-260 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central government has encouraged grain-producing areas to
export highly finished products such as instant noodles instead of
food grain. In this way, farmers would be able to yield a higher
profit from growing grain crops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan May Consider Moratorium on Debt Repayment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Finance Minister Sirtaj Aziz said
Wednesday that Pakistan might consider placing a moratorium on
debt repayment if the sanctions against it were prolonged and
applied to international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
"First of all it depends if the sanctions last more than three
months and whether they apply to international financial
institutions," he told journalists here after announcing the
results of Census '98.
</P>
<P>
If the sanctions are prolonged and are applied to the
international institutions, "then we will seriously consider a
moratorium on debt repayment," said the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said: "We are trying to avoid it but if we don't get new
money, we can not go servicing the debt."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question, Aziz said Pakistan gets 3 billion
U.S. dollars in aid every year and pays the same amount on annual
debt repayment.
</P>
<P>
"So if you get 1.5 billion dollars (as a result of sanctions
over the nuclear tests) how can you pay back 3 billion dollars on
annual debt. Nothing net has been left with us. All the assistance
we receive we pay back as debt servicing," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan has met every conditionality set by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) on June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday's meeting with IMF officials in Lahore, Aziz
declined to comment but said they wanted to help but they had been
prevented.
</P>
<P>
"Our stand is that the sanctions should not apply to
international institutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are persuading them that if you do this to a country which
has performed well, whose program was on track which was forced to
go for nuclear option as we did not initiate the whole thing, so
why create another crisis. You virtually (are) engineering the
crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF officials have been told that international
sanctions against Pakistan should not apply to the IMF. While they
substantially agree with it, they are subject to their own major
creditor countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
