<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, July 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Wednesday called on
Nigeria's military rulers to stick to the existing transition plan
to hand over civilian rule in October.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin, asked whether he
believed the October 1 target for a military handover should be
kept, said: "I'm not walking away from that timetable."
(US-Nigeria-Transition)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The United States and the three Baltic states agreed
Wednesday to strengthen their military cooperation at the first
session of the U.S.-Baltic Partnership Commission in Riga, Latvia.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique available here, the United States,
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania "stressed the importance of
continued U.S. military assistance for improving self-defense
capabilities" of the three states.
</P>
<P>
They also vowed to continue efforts of integrating the Baltic
states into European and trans-Atlantic institutions such as the
European Community, NATO and the World Trade Organization.
(US-Baltic States-Military Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States has intensified its effort to
revive the deadlocked Middle East peace process, the State
Department said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman James Rubin told reporters that Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright had called Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu four times over the weekend, twice on Tuesday and once
on Wednesday, each time for a half-hour to an hour.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Albright had stepped up pressure on Israel to
accept a U.S. proposal, turning an additional 13 percent of the
West Bank over to the Palestinian Authority. (US-Mideast-Albright)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Disturbances characterized by bonfires and
vehicle-attacking along major streets in parts of Nigeria's
commercial capital Lagos seem to have calmed down Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Violence began Tuesday night shortly after the news of the
sudden death of Nigeria's prominent political detainee Moshood
Abiola spread from the capital Abuja. (Nigeria-Calm in Lagos)
</P>
