<HEADLINE> Security Council Concerned about Findings on Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Members of the U.N. Security
Council on Wednesday expressed concern about the conclusions of a
recent report by the U.N. Secretary-general's human rights
investigative team in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The report, which points to evidence that killings in the
country constitute crimes against humanity, was considered by
the council in closed consultations here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press following consultations, the council
president Sergey Lavrov of the Russian Federation, said members
had expressed concern about the conclusions of the report and were
beginning to think about the council's reaction in the light of
its mandate to maintain international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
In a letter transmitting the report to the council,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan highlights the team's conclusion that
the killings by the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the
Liberation of the Congo (AFDL) constituted crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
Annan withdrew the team in April because of Congo's lack of
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
