<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls on Nigeria to Stick to Transition Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Wednesday
called on Nigeria's military rulers to stick to the existing
transition plan to hand over civilian rule in October.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin, asked whether he
believed the October 1 target for a military handover should be
kept, said: "I'm not walking away from that timetable."
</P>
<P>
"I mean, that is the existing transition plan ... I'm aware
of no reason why we would like it extended," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House spokesman Mike McCurry expressed
concern over the outbreak of violence following Tuesday's sudden
death of opposition leader Moshood Abiola.
</P>
<P>
"The untimely death of Chief Abiola has given rise to
uncertainty about the conditions for the political transition
back to democracy that the United States and the world community
so anxiously desires," he said at a briefing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
