<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Bureau Reports Successful Dress Rehearsal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Administration officials
Wednesday proclaimed a number of dress rehearsals for Census 2000
successful.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to report that we have met or exceeded our
expectations at each site," Acting Census Director James F. Holmes
said Wednesday at a press briefing here.
</P>
<P>
But Secretary William M. Daley of the Commerce Department, the
bureau's parent agency, warned that while the three practice
counts went well, congressional delays in funding the agency could
jeopardize the main event, scheduled to start for April 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
A dispute over methods to be used in the count among
legislators could stall action on the bureau's budget.
</P>
<P>
"They ought to separate out the political fight from the actual
running and operation of the census," Daley said. "If Congress is
going to have a fight and vote on what method should be used, they
should do that and not hold the Census Bureau hostage."
</P>
<P>
In the dress rehearsals the bureau used the traditional system
in one area and its proposed sampling technology in others. The
initial work is the same for both methods, sending out
questionnaires and contacting people who fail to respond.
</P>
<P>
Congressional Republicans are concerned that sampling will
increase the count of groups that tend to vote Democratic. Since
the Census results are used to distribute seats in the House of
Representatives and draw congressional district lines, they fear
this could lead to a loss of seats in the House.
</P>
<P>
Sampling involves the use of a sample of people missed in the
original count to estimate the number and characteristics of
others who have not been counted.
</P>
<P>
Contending that this doesn't meet the Constitutional
requirement for an enumeration, Republicans have filed suit to
block that method.
</P>
<P>
Because the Census is a massive undertaking that requires much
planning and preparation, Daley is pressing for prompt approval of
the agency's spending plans so it can be ready, regardless of
which method is finally chosen.
</P>
<P>
The overall cost of Census 2000 is expected to be about four
billion dollars if sampling is used and 4.7 billion dollars if the
traditional head count is taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
