<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Gun-Safety Measures in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday called on states and the U.S. Congress to impose stiffer
penalties against gun owners who let their weapons fall into the
hands of children and prevent handgun sales to minors.
</P>
<P>
Clinton make the call following a series of school shootings in
various states in the country that resulted in 15 deaths and
dozens of injuries.
</P>
<P>
The president also pledged federal assistance to a Maryland
program aimed at tracing every gun seized by police.
</P>
<P>
"As parents, public officials, citizens, we simply cannot allow
easy access to weapons that kill," Clinton said at a ceremony that
put a human face on the problem of gun violence in schools.
</P>
<P>
"This recent series of killings in our schools has seared the
heart of America about as much as anything I can remember in a
long, long time," Clinton said. "It is still too easy for deadly
weapons to wind up in the hands of children... and then, to lead
to tragedy."
</P>
<P>
In addition, the U.S. Treasury Department, through its Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, will join with the state of
Maryland in the gun-tracing program.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also highlighted the warning-sign regulations,
developed in response to an order by the president in June 1997
and released by the Treasury Department on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
