<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Steps up Pressure on Israel over Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
intensified its effort to revive the deadlocked Middle East
peace process, the State Department said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman James Rubin told reporters that Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright had called Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu four times over the weekend, twice on Tuesday and once
on Wednesday, each time for a half-hour to an hour.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, we are in an intensified effort," he said. But he
cautioned that "We have no knowledge that this will yield
success."
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Albright had stepped up pressure on Israel to
accept a U.S. proposal, turning an additional 13 percent of the
West Bank over to the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has so far rejected the proposal on the pretext
that it would jeopardize Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
This week he indicated, however, that he was close to
accepting the U.S. proposal provided the Palestinian Authority
commits itself to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Albright also talked once to Palestinian leader Yasir Arafat
on Wednesday in her "intensive end-game negotiations" to seek
stronger Palestinian measures against terrorism, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Albright hoped that Israel and the Palestinians would
immediately enter into the final status negotiations once the
two parties reach agreement over Israel's withdrawal and
Palestinians' measures against terrorism, Rubin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
