<HEADLINE> U.S. Provides Food Aid to Southern Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that it would provide another 9,390 tons of food, valued
at almost 16 million U.S. dollars, to combat famine in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Brian Atwood, administrator of the Agency for International
Development (AID) said the latest U.S. contribution, which brings
U.S. aid in Sudan to over 75 million U.S. Dollars this year, would
go to meet the most urgent needs of 1.2 million people.
</P>
<P>
Atwood also said it would donate 1.5 million U.S. dollars to
expand air and road deliveries of food through the U.N. World Food
Program and 2 million U.S. dollars to the U.N. Children's Fund to
support air operations.
</P>
<P>
In southern Sudan, more than 2.5 million people are in dire
need for food aid because of a 15-year North-South civil war,
coupled with drought last year and a further rain failure this
year, according to the World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
Politically, the United States strongly opposes the Islamic
government in Khartoum and provides diplomatic and moral support
to rebels in the South.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
