<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Says Abiola's Death "Tragedy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's new leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar Wednesday night expressed condolence to the
death of detained opposition leader Moshood Abiola who died on
the brink of his release, describing Abiola's death as a
"national tragedy".
</P>
<P>
In a national broadcast on the state TV, the Nigerian
Television Authority, at 7:00 p.m., Abubakar said the death of
Abiola is "a national tragedy and "one of the saddest moment of
our life."
</P>
<P>
Abubakar stressed the need of peace and stability in the
nation's transition to democracy. He reiterated his
determination to re-establish the professional image of the
Nigerian army and to have it play its traditional role in the
coming democratic order.
</P>
<P>
According to Abubakar, the country's supreme ruling body, the
Provisional Ruling Council, was scheduled to meet Wednesday to
decide on Abiola's release as a result of consultations between
Abiola and the government on one hand, and those between Abiola
and representatives of the international community as well as
members of his family on the other hand.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said the government has ordered an autopsy to
establish the actual cause of Abiola's death, and the result will
be known in due course.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the autopsy is being undertaken with the
cooperation of Abiola's family and the participation of
pathologists from Britain, the United States and Canada, as
requested by his family.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has appealed to Nigerians to remain calm to shun
violences, saying that the national grief of Abiola's death
should not be the cause of unlawfulness and wide destruction of
innocent people's property.
</P>
<P>
Extending condolences to the Abiola family, friends and
associates, the general promised he will address the nation again
on the general character of his government in due course.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, however, failed to address the nation on his
dissolution of cabinet, the Federal Executive Council, at a
meeting of the Provisional Ruling Council early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, the believed winner of the annulled June 12, 1993
presidential election, reportedly died of heart attack Tuesday
afternoon during a meeting with Abubakar and a U.S. delegation
headed by Under-Secretary of State Thomas Pickering.
</P>
<P>
Abiola's sudden death on the eve of his anticipated release
has raised suspicions of foul play among his family and the
opposition. His daughter Wura Abiola, who is living the United
State, said she believed her father was murdered.
</P>
<P>
His death has sparked violence in Lagos, and Ibadan in the
southwest, the strongholds of his supporters. Unconfirmed reports
said at least 10 people have died, with many others injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
