<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Addis Ababa City Administration Warns Striking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Addis Ababa city
administration Wednesday warned that it would take legal measures
against taxi service providers if they do not resume service by
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The warning was given by the city administration after taxi
service providers went on strike Wednesday in protest of the new
traffic regulation which is effective from July 8, 1998, first
day of 1998/99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The Addis Ababa city administration was quoted by the
Ethiopian News Agency as saying that the strike is "illegal" and
any problems that might arise in the implementation of the
regulation could be resolved through discussion.
</P>
<P>
The administration said the strike that lasted throughout the
day has not won the recognition of two taxi owners associations
namely Nib and Segon.
</P>
<P>
It said it would take legal actions on the individuals who
organized and took part in the strike.
</P>
<P>
The administration announced last Friday a new road safety
regulation which will be implemented Wednesday. However, the new
regulation has been described by the two taxi owners associations
as "too stiff" and "punitive rather than preventive," according
to press reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Demands Continued Fiscal Discipline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Wim Duisenberg, president of the
European Central Bank (ECB), Wednesday warned that the 11
countries that will start the single European currency euro next
January must do more to reduce their budget deficits and national
debts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in Frankfurt, Duisenberg said he
was watching with concern how some countries were not using
"growth dividend" generated from their current economic upturn to
help lower budget deficits and debts.
</P>
<P>
Most euro member states must still make considerable efforts to
put their finance in order so as to ensure a stable euro,
Duisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
The new ECB leader's warning came as some European Union
countries appear to be slackening their efforts to rein in
deficits and debts, while an upturn in economic growth has eased
the pressure on budgets.
</P>
<P>
Officials from some countries have reportedly argued that the
increased revenues from economic growth should be used to finance
investment or job creation.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg, however, stressed that in the long run, a stable
common currency was the best precondition for growth and
employment.
</P>
<P>
Under EU criteria for joining the euro, countries are supposed
to run up budget deficit of no more than three percent of gross
domestic product (GDP), and have long-term debts of no more than
60 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
A stability pact linked to the monetary union accord also
stipulates that participants in the euro club that fail to adhere
to the criteria will face heavy financial penalties unless they
take immediate correction action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lagos Calms down Temporarily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Disturbances characterized by
bonfires and vehicle-attacking along major streets in parts of
Nigeria's commercial capital Lagos seem to have calmed down
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Violence began Tuesday night shortly after the news of the
sudden death of Nigeria's prominent political detainee Moshood
Abiola spread from the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Many of Abiola's angry and shocked supporters, mainly youths,
took to the streets, attacking cars, shops and burning tyres, in
protest against the death of the businessman/politician who was
expected to be freed very soon.
</P>
<P>
Abiola was detained in June 1994 after declaring himself
president of Nigeria. He was widely believed to have won the
presidential elections in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
A Yoruba from western Nigeria, Abiola had numerous supporters
in Lagos, a city with a population of some eight million.
</P>
<P>
The violence in the metropolis overnight was reported to leave
some ten persons dead and many others injured.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the Defense Headquarters, all the
police in the state and anti-riot soldiers at the Lagos Garrison
Command have been deployed to strategic points of the city.
</P>
<P>
Armoured personnel carriers are also seen in some major bus
stops.
</P>
<P>
All the efforts were made to stop unnecessary loss of lives
and the destruction, looting and vandalization of property, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
So far on Wednesday, most streets which are usually bustling
have remained desert, while the majority of shops, banks and
other businesses are closed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Col. Mohammed Marwa, the military administrator of
Lagos state, has urged protesting youths to be calm and accept
the death of Abiola as "an act of God".
</P>
<P>
"Please don't engage in disturbances as nothing will be
achieved by it. I also wish to appeal to parents and guardians
not to allow their children and wards to be used by unscrupulous
elements to ferment trouble," Marwa told Lagos citizens in a
broadcast earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Marwa said he was informed of Abiola's death by the head of
state General Abdulsalam Abubakar at 6:00 p.m. Tuesday afternoon,
when he was at a meeting of the National Council of States to
discuss the military government's transition to civil rule
program in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
He said the head of state ordered him to go back to Lagos
immediately to prepare for possible social disorder in the city,
believed to be the stronghold of Abiola's supporters and
sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
Extending his condolence to Abiola's sudden death, Marwa said
the state government was in contact with members of Abiola's
family on burial plans, pledging that it would fully participate
in all the arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Some family members of Abiola met him in Abuja Monday and the
private meeting lasted some 90 minutes, Marwa disclosed, adding
that he attended a meeting the same day which was chaired by
Abubakar to discuss the release of Abiola and other political
detainees.
</P>
<P>
To add weight to the state government's action, Marwa has
ordered the closure of schools in Lagos until Friday in honor of
Abiola.
</P>
<P>
However, observers believe the current calmness in Lagos is
fragile because the exact cause of Abiola's death is not yet
known until the end of an autopsy now going on with the help of
experts from Britain, the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the contradictions between Nigerians in the south
and north, which is the fundamental cause of the country's power
struggle, is far from being settled.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar announced Wednesday afternoon the dissolution of the
country's cabinet. Observers noted it may be a step taken by the
northerner-dominated military to show good relations with the
people in the south.
</P>
<P>
The new head of state may want to create room for southerners
to enter the government as representatives of the people in those
areas, one analyst said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Advance into World Cup Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SAINT-DENIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- France scored a 2-1 victory to
advance into the final of the France'98 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The French team played more aggressively than in the first half
than their Croatia opponents.
</P>
<P>
But it was the Croatia who opened the scoring 26 seconds into
the second half as Aljosa Asanovic put Davor Suker clear and the
latter beat the French goal-keeper Fabien Barthez to take a 1-0 lead
for his team.
</P>
<P>
Only one minute later, Lilian Thuram levelled the score and the
host team were greatly boosted by the equaliser.
</P>
<P>
At the 70th minute, Thuram scored again as he capitalized a
mistake by the Croatia defenders and netted an powerful right-foot shot.
</P>
<P>
But the French team's lead was almost blown off by defender
Laurent Blanc who was sent off at the 75th minute.
</P>
<P>
Blanc punched Croatia defender Slaven Bilic on the face and then
argued with the referee. That earned him a red card immediately.
</P>
<P>
Playing with 10 men, the French team still stick to attack and
could have scored more goals. But Zidane's shots were just wide.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the French team enter the World Cup final.
They will take on defending champions Brazil on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980709.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
